<HEAD>Abortion Rights Battle Poses Risks, Opportunities, Female Politicians
Told</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY R. SANDOK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Renewed threats to abortion rights should be viewed as a significant opportunity to unify the women's movement, speakers told the National Women's Political Caucus `` We must bring the same spirit to the fight for abortion rights that we brought to the fight for the ERA -LRB- Equal Rights Amendment -RRB-,'' <PERSON> Eleanor </PERSON> <PERSON> Holmes </PERSON> <PERSON> Norton </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Georgetown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> law professor, told the caucus' biennial convention on Friday. `` That means leaving no state unturned. It means the same grunt work this caucus did in state after state for the ERA. There is no shortcut, no magic pill, no easy way,'' she said. `` Ironically, despite internal and perhaps inevitable disagreement over tactics, this issue can and will bring greater unity.'' <PERSON> Norton </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bella </PERSON> <PERSON> Abzug </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> congresswoman from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and a founder of the 18-year-old caucus, said they expect abortion will be the issue that prompts young women to join the fight for women's rights in numbers not seen since the movement's peak during the 1970s It presents `` an opportunity to revitalize the movement so it may complete the mammoth job that remains to secure women their rights and their freedoms,'' said <PERSON> Norton </PERSON>, former chairwoman of the <ORGANIZATION> Equal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opportunities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Norton </PERSON> said the caucus `` must not underestimate the need for a resilient, confident mass movement of broad appeal if we are to prevail on the troublesome issue of reproductive choices.'' But, she added, `` we must avoid the single-issue ... approach of the anti-choice crowd'' when seeking to stop efforts to impose abortion restrictions authorized by a recent <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision. <PERSON> Abzug </PERSON> said the threat of abortion restrictions will mobilize the nation's young people like no issue since the <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> War: `` Abortion is the <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> of this generation for young people everywhere.'' A woman's right to decide whether to have children `` free from intrusion or coercion by government or church or the outright violence of any individual is as precious and individual a liberty as the right to speak and the right to believe and the right to pray,'' <PERSON> Abzug </PERSON> said. Without the free exercise of that right, she said, `` no woman can be deemed to be fully free or equal.'' `` The idea that the unborn fetus is -LRB- entitled to -RRB- protection from the moment of conception is biologically ignorant and philosophically outrageous,'' <PERSON> Abzug </PERSON> said. `` No civilized nation can be allowed to declare an unborn fetus to be a person under the Constitution before women are declared to be persons under the Constitution.'' Although the number of women holding elective and appointive offices has increased during the past two decades, the gains have been incremental, <PERSON> Abzug </PERSON> said. `` At the rate we're going it will take 410 years to get equal numbers of men and women in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>,'' she said. `` We have ... allowed ourselves to lower our sights and lower our demands. I believe we have to begin thinking in new ways.'' <PERSON> Abzug </PERSON> suggested asking both political parties to commit all open seats to women until equity is reached in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> House and pursuing the idea of having one of each state's two <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> senators be a woman.
</TEXT>
