<HEAD>Billie Holiday Remembrance Opens `Classical Jazz'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Singer Billie Holiday and tenor saxophonist <PERSON> Lester </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON> were remembered by three singers and three tenor players at the opening of <ORGANIZATION> Lincoln </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>'s third annual `` Classical Jazz'' series. The first of six concerts, each centered around outstanding figures from the history of jazz, was sold out Friday night at <ORGANIZATION> Alice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tully </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hall </ORGANIZATION>. The performers were <PERSON> Abby </PERSON> <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON> with <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Heath </PERSON>, <PERSON> Etta </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> with <ORGANIZATION> Houston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Person </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Shirley </PERSON> <PERSON> Horn </PERSON> with <LOCATION> Buck </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>. Miss <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON>, who had the longest set, has an individual timbre, sounding not at all like Billie Holiday. Her delivery is warm, open and generous. She seems a balance of tough and vulnerable and she seems to be giving of herself. She's mesmerizing, pulling the audience with her into the world of Billie Holiday's songs. <PERSON> Heath </PERSON> and each member of Miss <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON>'s trio stretched out in interesting solos. <PERSON> Etta </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> and <PERSON> Houston </PERSON> <PERSON> Person </PERSON>, who have been performing together since 1976, have their pattern set with his sax providing melodic fills between her lines of singing. Miss <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> wraps her words and syllables around the instrumental music, the way Miss Holiday did. She also had a trio on stage. Pianist <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Braham </PERSON> captured the imagination. <PERSON> Shirley </PERSON> <PERSON> Horn </PERSON> played her own piano accompaniment, with bassist and drummer. <PERSON> Buck </PERSON> <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> played saxophone with them on every other song. Miss <PERSON> Horn </PERSON>'s approach is lightness. If the other two singers were airplanes, she was a glider, touching down occasionally. Then right away, and in no hurry, she'd lift off again.
</TEXT>
