<HEAD>Hurricane Dean Drifts North Away from Islands</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf with 10:30 p.m. EDT position.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hurricane Dean drifted northward Friday in the open <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> after veering away from northern <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> islands and the southeastern <LOCATION> Bahamas </LOCATION>, forecasters said. `` It may strengthen a little bit. There are changes that are taking place around it,'' said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheets </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hurricane </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in suburban <LOCATION> Coral </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gables </LOCATION>. At 10:30 p.m. EDT, <PERSON> Dean </PERSON>'s winds of 85 mph were centered near 23.0 north latitude and 64.91 <LOCATION> west </LOCATION> <LOCATION> longitude </LOCATION>, about 600 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Bermuda </LOCATION>. The hurricane was moving north at about 12 mph, forecasters said. `` Our latest reconnaissance positions indicate that indeed it may start a little bit more fast speed toward the north, and you can see that on the satellite,'' Sheets said. A weakening of upper atmosphere currents that steer the storm kept <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> away from the islands Thursday, after it initially headed toward the <LOCATION> Virgin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>. The hurricane was moving very slowly. `` We're still expecting it to turn to the north and then eventually go to the northeast,'' said forecaster <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Gross </PERSON>. Asked about the storm's potential for hitting <LOCATION> Bermuda </LOCATION> in about three days, he said: `` They're very easy to miss.'' The second hurricane of the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> season became a tropical storm Monday night and was reclassified a hurricane Tuesday when its maximum sustained wind speed passed 74 mph.
