<HEAD>Dozens Injured When Crowd Presses into Concert Grandstand</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than 50 people were injured when a crowd trying to get into a standing-room-only area for a Friday evening grandstand concert at the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> State </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fair </LOCATION> pressed into the area before it was opened. State Highway Patrol troopers at the scene said most of the injuries were minor. <PERSON> Shane </PERSON> <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON>, director of public relations, said 58 people were treated at the fair; about a dozen later were taken to hospitals. Doctors' Hospital North nursing supervisor <PERSON> Melanie </PERSON> <PERSON> Crader </PERSON> said eight teen-agers were treated for minor injuries. `` I think there was one broken foot, but it was pretty minor stuff. There were varying complaints,'' she said. After the disturbance, Gov. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Celeste </PERSON> met with fair officials and managers of the acts scheduled to appear Friday night. Following the meeting, the manager for one of the acts, New Kids on the Block, announced that the entertainment would be presented one act at a time, and if authorities felt the crowd was getting unruly, the rest of the show would be canceled. After the announcement, <PERSON> Celeste </PERSON> walked along the perimeter of the grandstand, telling concertgoers to `` Be cool and pass it back.'' Trooper <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Esslinger </PERSON> said he could not estimate the size of the crowd for the 8 p.m. concert. The crowd had been building all day, and the grandstand was largely filled by late afternoon, witnesses said. The standing-room-only area had not been opened when the crowd broke for the seats, witnesses said. A thunderstorm broke shortly after the crowd rushed into the area, adding to the confusion.
