<FIRST>r a AM-AIDSTest     08-05 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS Test,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Early-Diagnosis Test Finds AIDS Virus Instead of Body's Reaction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Abbott </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION> is marketing a new test that detects the AIDS virus rather than the body's response to the virus and can reveal infection weeks earlier than currently used tests, the company said Friday. AIDS-virus tests now in use detect the presence of antibodies _ proteins manufactured by white blood cells to fight invading organisms. Antibodies usually appear in a person's system six to 10 weeks after infection. The new test detects AIDS antigens _ proteins on the surface of the invading virus. The new test can signal the presence of the antigens about two weeks after infection, a spokesman for the North Chicago-based company said. ` This test complements the antibody test. It does not replace the antibody test,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Kessler </PERSON>, associate professor of medicine and director of the HIV treatment program at Rush-Presbyterian-St. <PERSON> Luke </PERSON>'s Medical Center Test was approved Thursday for commercial sale by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, making it the only approved test for the AIDS virus in the country. Though antigens are the first detectable sign of infection, they effectively `` disappear'' with the appearance of antibodies, which remain in the body. The antigen test is thus not always able to reveal the presence of infection. Antigens only reappear when the virus becomes more active, a possible signal that the infected person will get sick, either with immune problems, with a mild form of AIDS known as AIDS-related complex or with full-blown AIDS, said <PERSON> Kessler </PERSON>. To identify which infected people are likely to develop symptoms _ some may be infected for years without any symptoms _ doctors can check patients with the new test every three or four months, said <PERSON> Abbott </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Weber </PERSON>. `` If you come up where the antigen test is positive, that might be the opportune moment to intervene with AZT or some form of antiviral therapy,'' <PERSON> Weber </PERSON> said. AZT, or zidovudine, is the only drug approved by the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> for fighting AIDS. <PERSON> Kessler </PERSON> said antigen-positive patients have a 75 percent chance of developing symptoms, compared with 29 percent for antigen-negative patients. The new test, available under the trade name HIV AG-1, is already under manufacture because is has previously been used to monitor the effectiveness of AZT. It will continue to be valuable for that purpose, <PERSON> Kessler </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Kessler </PERSON> said the test will probably cost $ 100 to $ 120 at the lab, which is `` not out of line'' with other laboratory tests for viruses.
</TEXT>
