nt than the 261-162 approval of the authorization bill. `` They have conformed,'' Rep. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Dickinson </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, ranking <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> member on <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, said of the two pieces of legislation. `` But that still makes it veto-bait in my opinion.'' <PERSON> Dickinson </PERSON> said he hoped that when members of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> meet early in September to craft a final version of the bill, the `` most egregious add-ons and deletions can be modified and limited to make it acceptable to the administration.'' Among the other final-day action taken by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>: _ The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> voted 99-0 to increase industry's financial liability for oil spills, create a nationwide system to clean up such accidents and establish a $ 1 billion trust fund to help compensate for damages The vote came less than five months after the tanker <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Valdez </ORGANIZATION> struck a reef in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON>, spilling 11 million gallons of oil. _ The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> approved a compromise plan providing $ 895 million to farmers who suffered crop losses caused by the drought and other weather-related problems <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration officials have indicated that the president will sign the legislation.
