 A $ 3.1 million judgment won by the widow of an <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> pilot killed in an F-16 jet crash in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> more than six years ago has been overturned by a three-judge federal appeals court panel. The widow, <PERSON> Janet </PERSON> <PERSON> Harduvel </PERSON> of <PERSON> Lutz </PERSON>, can petition the full 11th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> to reconsider the case. If the request is refused, she has said she plans to appeal to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. Retired <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Justice <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> <PERSON> Powell </PERSON> served on the appellate panel and wrote its opinion released Monday. The judgment was rendered by a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> jury in April 1987 against <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dynamics </ORGANIZATION>, the F-16 fighter jet contractor, on the grounds that the plane was defectively designed and manufactured. Mrs. <PERSON> Harduvel </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Acosta </PERSON>, told the appeals panel the plane had a severe electrical malfunction causing the crash into a mountain that killed Capt. <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Harduvel </PERSON> in November 1982. <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Dumbroff </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, D.C.-based attorney representing <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dynamics </ORGANIZATION>, asked for a reversal, contending the crash was a result of pilot error. The panel rejected the argument that there were de