<FIRST>r a PM-FreudLibel     08-05 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Freud Libel,0579</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Appeals Court Upholds Fabrication of Quotes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A psychologist intends to appeal a federal court ruling that allows a journalist quoting a public figure to make up a quote if the quote does not `` alter the substantive content'' of what was said. The 9th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> ruled on Friday that <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Masson </PERSON>, a former director of the <ORGANIZATION> Freud </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Archives </ORGANIZATION>, could not sue writer <PERSON> Janet </PERSON> <PERSON> Malcolm </PERSON> for $ 10.2 million over a <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Yorker </ORGANIZATION> magazine article and book that allegedly quoted him as saying many things he never said. The purported quotes included <PERSON> Masson </PERSON>'s self-description as an `` intellectual gigolo,'' his comment that after <PERSON> Sigmund </PERSON> <PERSON> Freud </PERSON> he would be regarded as `` the greatest analyst who ever lived,'' and a statement that he would have turned the <PERSON> Freud </PERSON> house into `` a place of sex, women, fun.'' In a libel suit by a public figure, who must prove that harmful statements were deliberately or recklessly false, quotations can be fabricated if they are `` rational interpretations of ambiguous remarks'' or `` do not alter the substantive content of unambiguous remarks,'' said the opinion by Judge <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Alarcon </PERSON>. He was joined in his opinion by Judge <PERSON> Cynthia </PERSON> <PERSON> Holcomb </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>. But the dissenter in the 2-1 decision, Judge <PERSON> Alex </PERSON> <PERSON> Kozinski </PERSON>, said fabricated quotes were the equivalent of lies. `` If authors are given license to invent quotations on the basis of what they perceive to be a speaker's character, there are no words whatsoever that they can not put into a subject's mouth,'' <PERSON> Kozinski </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Karl </PERSON> <PERSON> Olson </PERSON>, lawyer for <PERSON> Malcolm </PERSON> and her publishers, said the ruling vindicates his clients. He said they never conceded that any quotes had been made up or changed, other than `` a word here and a word there.'' <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Kleven </PERSON>, a lawyer for <PERSON> Masson </PERSON>, said the ruling would be appealed. `` We do n't think there's any need to allow that sort of alteration to protect the values that the First Amendment is designed to protect,'' he said. <PERSON> Masson </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION> resident, was fired in 1981 as director of the New York-based <ORGANIZATION> Freud </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Archives </ORGANIZATION>. He said he was fired and fell out of favor among psychoanalysts because he had written that <PERSON> Freud </PERSON>, the father of modern pscyhoanalysis, knew the evidence was to the contrary when he declared that women usually fantasized claims of childhood sexual abuse. His suit attacked <PERSON> Malcolm </PERSON>'s 1983 <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Yorker </ORGANIZATION> article, `` Trouble in the Archives,'' and her 1984 book, `` In the <ORGANIZATION> Freud </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Archives </ORGANIZATION>,'' on the struggle between <PERSON> Masson </PERSON> and directors of the archives over his views on <PERSON> Freud </PERSON>. <PERSON> Masson </PERSON> said <PERSON> Malcolm </PERSON> had maliciously painted a false picture of him by fabricating quotes, citing numerous statements that were not in her tape-recorded interviews. He also said he notified the New Yorker and the book publisher of the fabrications before publication. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Lynch </PERSON> dismissed the suit in 1987. An appeals court upheld his ruling. <PERSON> Kozinski </PERSON>, in his dissent, said the quotes distorted <PERSON> Masson </PERSON>'s taped statements: for example, he never called himself the greatest analyst, just the only one who held his views In addition, <PERSON> Kozinski </PERSON> said, journalists are supposed to vouch for the accuracy of the quotes they use. He also quoted <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Shawn </PERSON>, editor of the New Yorker at the time of <PERSON> Malcolm </PERSON>'s articles, as calling the magazine `` the most accurate publication not only in this country, but in the entire world.''
</TEXT>
