<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Actor <PERSON> Rob </PERSON> <PERSON> Lowe </PERSON> passed out after videotaping two young women having sex in his hotel room, and the women took the tape and began circulating copies of it the next day, <ORGANIZATION> Rolling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stone </ORGANIZATION> magazine reports. <PERSON> Lowe </PERSON> last week agreed to perform 20 hours of community service to avoid prosecution for allegedly seducing then 16-year-old <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Parsons </PERSON>. Her mother drew attention to the video of Miss <PERSON> Parsons </PERSON> and the girl's friend, <PERSON> Tara </PERSON> <PERSON> Seburt </PERSON>, when she filed suit in May against <PERSON> Lowe </PERSON>. The civil suit is pending. The movie star and Miss <PERSON> Parsons </PERSON> met at a downtown disco during the 1988 Democratic National Convention. Rolling Stone, in its Aug. 24 edition, quoted the dance club's publicity director, <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>, as saying Miss <PERSON> Seburt </PERSON> called her the morning after the tape was made to tell her about it Ms. <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> said <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Seburt </PERSON> told her that when <PERSON> Lowe </PERSON> passed out, she and <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Parsons </PERSON> left the hotel room, taking $ 200 from his wallet, along with pills and the tape. The young women arranged through a friend at a hair salon where they worked to have someone make copies, the magazine said. <PERSON> Lowe </PERSON>, who is filming a movie called `` Bad Influence,'' declined to be interviewed for the article, and his publicists refused to comment. Rolling <PERSON> Stone </PERSON> said the videotape consists of three segments, starting with a sex escapade involving <PERSON> Lowe </PERSON> and a male and a female friend in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> before he went to the convention. The second segment shows <PERSON> Lowe </PERSON>'s visit to an <ORGANIZATION> Atlanta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Braves </ORGANIZATION> baseball game with <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Assemblyman <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayden </PERSON> and the third shows the encounter with the two young women, which took place at a hotel on July 18, 1988.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Rolling Stones will bring their `` Steel Wheels'' tour to <ORGANIZATION> Syracuse </ORGANIZATION>'s Carrier Dome for one appearance to make up for the canceled tour opener in <LOCATION> Buffalo </LOCATION>, stadium officials said. <ORGANIZATION> Syracuse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> officials said they expected to sign a formal contract by Monday for the Sept. 22 concert. The canceled <LOCATION> Buffalo </LOCATION> appearance upset <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> rock fans, who heard the show was called off because of poor attendance at a concert by The Who at <ORGANIZATION> Buffalo </ORGANIZATION>'s Rich Stadium on July 18. That show drew slightly more than 30,000 spectators in a stadium seating 89,000 people. The Stones' tour, which starts Sept. 1 in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, will take them to <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>; East Troy, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Raleigh </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Syracuse </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Musicians who quit <PERSON> Lionel </PERSON> <PERSON> Hampton </PERSON>'s band because of inadequate pay are demanding that he rehire them, and a musicians union tried to picket the band leader's rehearsal space. Twelve of <PERSON> Hampton </PERSON>'s 16 musicians refused to board an airplane for <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> on July 25, saying they wanted more money per performance than <PERSON> Hampton </PERSON> was offering. <PERSON> Hampton </PERSON> hired Japanese musicians while he was in the Far East and hired Americans when he returned last week, said publicist <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>. Local 802 of the <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Musicians </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Greater </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> sent a telegram to <PERSON> Hampton </PERSON> on Thursday saying his striking members were ready to come back to work pending negotiations, said union President <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Glasel </PERSON>. No answer came back, <PERSON> Glasel </PERSON> said. The union tried to picket <PERSON> Hampton </PERSON> on Friday but he did not show up at his rehearsal. `` Here's a union that got them to strike and now wants to get their jobs back,'' said <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>. `` He's willing to take them back, but <PERSON> Lionel </PERSON>'s got a new band.'' <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said the striking musicians would be the first hired should the new band members quit, adding that two of the 12 striking members had rejoined the band.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BIG TIMBER, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
