<HEAD>Lawyer: Congress Would Be Wrong in Taking Driver's Licenses from
Dropouts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK PAXTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> would be making a mistake by following <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>'s lead and barring high school dropouts from driving, said the lawyer for the teen-ager who failed in his challenge of the state law. <LOCATION> Kanawha </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Circuit Judge <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Zakaib </PERSON> upheld the law Friday, saying the government has a compelling interest in keeping children in class. The case involved an appeal filed by 17-year-old <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Means </PERSON>, who lost his license when he dropped out shortly after his 16th birthday. The law has drawn national attention, and on Thursday an <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> congressman introduced a bill for a similar nationwide statute. Means' lawyer, <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Butch </PERSON>, said that would be a mistake. <PERSON> Butch </PERSON> said inner-city youths often do n't have access to cars and wo n't care if their driver's licenses are taken away. `` White, suburban kids will go back to school so they can have the car on Saturday night and go cruising,'' he said. `` Kids in the inner-city are going to have no reason to stay in school because they can use the <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Avenue </LOCATION> subway.'' Means, whose 16-year-old wife is expecting their first child this month, lives on the outskirts of <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION> and says he ca n't get a job to support his family without driving privileges He overslept, <PERSON> Butch </PERSON> said, and did not attend Friday's hearing. Means does not have a home telephone and messages left with his family were n't returned. In his ruling, <PERSON> Zakaib </PERSON> said Means was not denied due process because he was granted a hearing by the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vehicles </ORGANIZATION> before his license was suspended. He also ruled that Means failed to prove he was forced to drop out of school by circumstances beyond his control, an exemption provided by the state law. Noting that 40 percent of the state's residents have an eighth-grade education or less, <PERSON> Zakaib </PERSON> said the law is a legitimate way for the state to persuade students to stay in school. `` The failure to graduate or complete a secondary education not only adversely affects the juvenile, it affects the society as a whole,'' <PERSON> Zakaib </PERSON> said. Assistant Attorney General <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>, who represented the state at Friday's hearing, said 400 dropouts whose licenses were suspended because of the new law returned to school last year. The state normally has 5,000 dropouts each school year, but in 1988-89 the number was just 3,400 to 3,500, <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> said. `` This ruling establishes that driving is a conditional privilege and not a basic right,'' said Attorney General <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>. `` Further, this law acts as a positive tool in building a solid foundation for a prosperous and more educated generation.''
