<FIRST>r w PM-PuertoRicoReport     08-05 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Puerto Rico Report,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Statehood for Puerto Rico Could Raise Social Welfare Costs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 If <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION> becomes a state, federal spending for some social welfare programs could rise, a congressional study says. The study, released Friday by Sen. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, who requested it, looked at the effects of a proposal for a referendum on the status of <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>, currently before <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. The Congressional Research Report analyzed what would happen to some social welfare programs if <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION> were to become a state; be granted independence; or receive `` enhanced'' commonwealth status under which federal grant-in-aid programs could be consolidated and streamlined. For example, replacing <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>'s program of aid to the aged, blind or disabled with the <ORGANIZATION> Supplemental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Income </ORGANIZATION> program would significantly expand the eligible population, increasing benefits by as much as tenfold, said the report. The study did n't make definitive cost or budget estimates but looked at the general implications of the alternatives. Demographically, <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION> is younger, poorer and suffers higher unemployment than any of the 50 states, the study noted. The programs that would have the greatest impact if extended to <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION> as a state are food stamps, Supplemental Security Income and the earned income tax credit, for which benefits are nationally uniform and not set by the states, the study found. Currently, SSI is not available in <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>. The program, which is administered by the <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, guarantees a minimum level of cash income to the needy blind, aged and disabled. Instead, <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION> operates an assistance program of aid to such people, although disability payments are restricted to those age 18 or older. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government pays 75 percent of <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>'s assistance payments to the aged, blind or disabled up to a specified limit, the report says. In fiscal 1987, <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION> qualified for a maximum of $ 12.9 million in matching funds, according to the study. But if <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION> were treated like the states, <ORGANIZATION> SSI </ORGANIZATION> would replace the current system, providing much larger benefits but setting much higher eligibility limits, the report says. Furthermore, SSI would cover disabled children not currently included. If <PERSON> Puerto </PERSON> <PERSON> Rico </PERSON> became a state, the federal food stamp program would replace its Nutrition Assistance Program, under which eligible people receive cash benefits. All benefits would have to be issued in coupons, and while it is not clear what the levels would be, they would be higher than in the rest of the country, according to the report.
</TEXT>
