<BYLINE>By BARRY MASSEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration is embracing a nearly $ 900 million package of federal disaster aid for farmers passed by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to cover crop losses this year from severe weather. Agriculture Secretary <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> indicated Friday the president would sign the legislation and he vowed to implement the relief program `` as promptly and fairly as we possibly can.'' Passage of the measure by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> ended weeks of uncertainty for farm-state lawmakers, who worried they would have to return home empty-handed for a month-long recess. Now they can assure farmers that federal relief checks will be available to cover expenses for the fall planting season. `` When our farmers suffer catastrophic loss, whether it's due to drought, flood or other disastrous weather, we must keep our pact with those who work the land,'' Sen. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON>, D-Vt., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said before the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> approved the measure on a voice vote and forwarded it to the White House The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> passed the bill earlier in the day without a recorded vote. In general, farmers can qualify for federal payments if they suffer crop losses from 35 percent to 50 percent because of weather-related disasters. The measure also offers payments to livestock producers facing drought-related feed and water shortages for their herds. Key eligibility and payment provisions in the assistance package are identical to legislation approved Wednesday by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. The bill is projected to cost about $ 895 million. `` It seems to me that the final outcome is about as sound as could have been expected under the circumstances,'' said <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON>. The legislation is aimed primarily at farmers in portions of the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION> and western Corn Belt, which have not recovered from the drought of 1988, and in the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION>, where flooding has destroyed rice and cotton. The bill has different eligibility standards for various crops but in all cases, producers would receive payments designed to cover 65 percent of their lost income from crop losses. In most instances, the projected income levels will be based on federal crop subsidies or average market prices farmers would have received had they not suffered losses. Lawmakers intend to pay for the relief package with savings from commodity subsidy programs, which are costing less because of higher market prices this year from weather-shrunken harvests. Last year, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> approved $ 3.9 billion in assistance for farmers hurt by drought. Supporters of this year's legislation said continued severe weather required another relief package but they pledged to improve the federal crop insurance program to alleviate the need for agricultural disaster aid in the future.
