<SECOND>PM-Senate-Oil Spills,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Approves Oil-Spill Bill</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Congress Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Responding to the Exxon Valdez oil spill, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> has passed environmental-protection legislation hailed by Majority Leader <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> as reducing `` the potential for damage to our nation.'' The measure boosts companies' liability for oil spills, creates a nationwide system to clean them up and establishes a $ 1 billion trust fund to help compensate for damages. Similar legislation is pending in the House. Such legislation had been under consideration for years, but the issue took on a new sense of urgency after the tanker struck <LOCATION> Bligh </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Reef </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON>, rupturing the ship's hull and spilling 11 million gallons of oil that stained the coastline. Added impetus came from two smaller-scale spills over a 24-hour period off <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, in the <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> and in the <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> Ship Channel. `` The purpose of this bill is to make sure that we never again allow an oil spill to become an ecological disaster,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Max </PERSON> <PERSON> Baucus </PERSON>, D-Mont., the bill's floor manager `` This legislation, when enacted into law, will discourage such oil spills in the future and reduce the potential for damage to our nation,'' said <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Maine </LOCATION>, who worked for passage of oil-spill legislation for eight years. `` And if they do occur, they will be cleaned up and compensated much more readily than has been the case,'' he said. The bill was approved 99-0, with Sen. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Durenberger </PERSON>, R-Minn., not voting The legislation directs that contingency plans be drawn for dealing with oil spills on land and water and requires the establishment of cleanup teams with pre-placed equipment. The $ 1 billion trust fund will be financed by a 3-cent-a-barrel fee _ or tax _ on all domestic and imported petroleum. The bill provides for increasing the limit of compensation for each oil spill from $ 500 million to $ 1 billion. In <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, Gov. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> praised the action. `` This bill is a major step forward for <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> and all other coastal states whose residents face enormous economic, environmental and human damage from oil spills,'' <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> said in Fairbanks. `` This bill wo n't end the suffering, but it will make major spills less likely and the response to them quicker and better.'' In acting on a series of amendments, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> sharply raised an owner's liability for compensating for oil spills and their destruction of property and the environment. The legislation preserves the authority of the states to impose unlimited liability if they wish and to impose their own oil spill standards and requirements, set up cleanup or compensation funds and levy fees and penalties. It also gives the president extensive authority to take overall charge of cleanup efforts, including issuing orders to owners.
