<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Piedmont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> has suspended two mechanics who are suspected of having accidentally left wheel chocks in both wing wheel wells of a jet that was forced to make an emergency landing in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>. The mechanics, whose names were not released, were suspended without pay pending an investigation by the airline of the incident, said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shipley </PERSON>, spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, headquartered in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. He estimated the airline's investigation would take four days and said, `` Until that time, the full disciplinary actions will not be determined.'' <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> owns <LOCATION> Piedmont </LOCATION> and was scheduled to merge the carrier into <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> today. The <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737, with 100 people aboard left <LOCATION> National </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> bound for <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION>, on Wednesday with a stop in <LOCATION> Charlotte </LOCATION>. It was diverted to <LOCATION> Greensboro </LOCATION> when the crew could n't get the landing gear down. No one was injured in the emergency landing. Triangular rubber blocks about called wheel chocks, about 2 -LCB- feet on a side, are used to keep the plane from rolling while it is on the ground. <PERSON> Phillip </PERSON> <PERSON> Powell </PERSON>, an investigator for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, said Thursday a 2 -LCB- - foot wheel chock had been found in the left wheel well immediately after the landing and investigators found evidence _ bent hydraulic lines _ that a chock in the right well was thrown out during maneuvers to shake the gear loose The two mechanics were assigned to check the plane Tuesday night, and during that check, said <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Golden </PERSON>, director of the safety board's regional office in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, the aircraft was moved six times. The chocks were apparently placed in the wells during one of those moves, he said. Ground crews sometimes stuff the chocks in the wheel well while moving planes, <PERSON> Powell </PERSON> said, a practice he called `` not a normal procedure.'' <PERSON> Powell </PERSON> said routine preflight inspection should have included checking the wheel compartments. Pilot <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Fuda </PERSON> told investigators he delegated the walk-around inspection to First Officer <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Curtis </PERSON> before takeoff. Fuda landed the jet on its right main gear, then touched the nose wheel down before settling the plane onto its left engine and skidding to a halt on the 10,000-foot runway, a shower of sparks coming from the scraping metal. Only the left engine, suspended below the wing, was damaged and the plane is expected to be returned to service after repairs.
