<HEAD>Bush Voices Support for Nicaraguan Rebels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> met with leaders of the Nicaraguan Contras to reinforce his support for their cause on the eve of today's meeting of <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> presidents to discuss disbanding the rebel force. Contra commander <PERSON> Enrique </PERSON> <PERSON> Bermudez </PERSON>, Contra directorate member <PERSON> Aristides </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON> and other leaders told <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> at the 20-minute meeting Friday that any demobilization must be tied to democratic reforms by <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s leftist government. `` They said if worse comes to worse, they're prepared to continue their struggle,'' said one administration official with knowledge of the meeting. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said `` he had supported them in the past and would continue to do so in the future,'' said the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity. According to Contra spokesman <PERSON> Bosco </PERSON> <PERSON> Matamoros </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> told the rebels he was urging the <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> presidents `` to preserve the integrity of the resistance'' until the Nicaraguan elections in February. <PERSON> Matamoros </PERSON> said that could mean the forces will remain encamped in <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> or move into <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> under conditions negotiated with the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION>. The White House meeting came as Nicaraguan President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> announced the domestic political opposition had agreed the Contras should disband. <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> said he will insist at the presidents' summit that camps housing 12,000 Contras in southern <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> be emptied. <PERSON> Matamoros </PERSON> said the rebels support the principles laid out in the <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> agreement announced in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>, but only if democratic reforms come first. The Central American presidents meet this weekend to work on specifics of their earlier agreement that the rebel army should be disbanded in return for reform in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration wants clear signs of democratic change before the Contras have to disband. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials have sidestepped the question of whether that means they want to keep the Contras together as a fighting force until the elections. `` You can argue over timing, but the answer is ... we feel that we should not be disintegrating the Contras until there's some assurance that the Sandinistas are meeting their democratic commitments,'' said White House press secretary <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> on Friday. Despite <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s vote of confidence, <ORGANIZATION> Matamoros </ORGANIZATION> said the rebels were upset with efforts from `` certain sectors in the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'' to divide the Contras, to speed demobilization. On <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> this week, Sen. <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Conn </LOCATION>., accused <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> of breaking an agreement with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> by urging the <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> presidents not to disband the Contras until after <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s Feb. 25 elections are concluded He warned <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> could off the $ 40 million aid package agreed to in a bipartisan accord between <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and congressional Democrats. The aid package is to keep the Contras supplied with non-lethal materials, but also can be used for voluntary relocation of rebels into <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>.
