<FIRST>r a PM-PrepaidTuition Bjt   08-05 0699</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Prepaid Tuition, Bjt,0722</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prepaid Tuition Plan Could Ease Parents' Worries Over College Costs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA WILKINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Like a lot of 5-year-olds, <PERSON> Jennifer </PERSON> <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> dreams of being many things when she grows up. Like a lot of parents, her father is already worried about paying for her education. `` She wants to be a fireman, she wants to be a nurse, she wants to be a doctor,'' said <PERSON> Ho </PERSON> <PERSON> Wang </PERSON>. With the introduction of the first national prepaid tuition program, <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> and other parents would have the option of paying now for their childrens' education _ a hedge against the rising costs of college. Under the National Prepaid Tuition Plan, <PERSON> Jennifer </PERSON> could be signed up for four years at a college before she can even pronounce its name. `` If I can have the opportunity of locking in the cost now without having to worry about the rate of return in future years, that would certainly be one of my considerations,'' <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> said in a telephone interview from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, where he works as a high-yield bond analyst. Universities such as <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> and <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON> have expressed interest in the plan, proposed by <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> Paul-based <ORGANIZATION> HEMAR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, but many others doubt whether it will ever get off the ground. Parents would pay a lump sum into independent investment funds selected by colleges with the help of <ORGANIZATION> HEMAR </ORGANIZATION>, which would charge 1 percent annually from the interest on the accounts. This would guarantee a four-year education, as long as the student was admitted to the college. <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> said he wondered whether highly competitive schools with tight admissions policies would ever partake in the plan. <ORGANIZATION> HEMAR </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> <PERSON> Stringer </PERSON> said he hoped the plan would be available this fall or winter pending rulings from the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Stringer </PERSON>, a former bank official and assistant director of financial aid at <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, said he envisions at least half of the nation's colleges, including top schools, signing up within five years. His company, which is affiliated with the <ORGANIZATION> Higher </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assistance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, a student loan insurer, mailed announcements about the plan last month to 1,350 schools. `` It gives them a recruiting device they did n't have before. Now they're in a position to recruit students at the age of birth if they're particularly aggressive,'' said <PERSON> Stringer </PERSON>. <PERSON> Stringer </PERSON> said the plan was flexible in allowing students to select schools other than the ones invested in by their parents. Such investments could be transferred in some cases, although parents would receive only their original investment back _ without interest _ if their children decided not to go to college, or selected schools not included in the plan. `` We worked pretty hard to make sure this plan had value to colleges as well as consumers,'' <PERSON> Stringer </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tuition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maintenance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Ann </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arbor </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, is introducing its own prepaid tuition plan, set up as a taxable mutual fund, to 30 colleges' alumni and supporters this month. Some experts have reservations about prepaid tuition, saying it would be extremely risky for colleges to participate in the plan. <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Hauptman </PERSON>, a policy consultant for the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, an association of about 1,400 colleges and universities, said it could mean that taxpayers or other students would have to pay if the invested prepayments do n't keep pace with rising tuition costs. <PERSON> Hauptman </PERSON> said a school that had n't done well in investing the prepayments might be tempted not to accept some of the children as students, because prepayment is no guarantee of admission. `` I really do think this tension between the admission office and the business office could become very problematic, where the economies of the plan may dictate who gets admitted to school,'' <PERSON> Hauptman </PERSON> said. State-sponsored prepaid tuition programs exist already in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Duquesne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> pioneered a plan four years ago allowing alumni parents to pay a lump sum guaranteeing four years of college assuming the child was accepted for admission. But <ORGANIZATION> Duquesne </ORGANIZATION> suspended the plan last year because of higher-than-expected tuition increases and lower-than-anticipated earnings on investments that rendered it uneconomical.
</TEXT>
