<FIRST>u w PM-S&amp;Ls Bjt 1stLd-Writethru 08-05 0828</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-S&amp;Ls, Bjt, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0446,800</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress Sends Landmark S&amp;L Bill To President</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmitting a0454 to note that it is 2nd graf that Corrects
vote to 175</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> sent a landmark savings and loan bailout to President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> early today after a frantic two days of wrangling over the finishing touches on the biggest financial rescue in history. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> passed the $ 159 billion legislation shortly after midnight Friday on a 201-175 vote, allowing weary members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to begin a monthlong vacation that had been threatened by a bitter fight with the administration over the financing of the package. House Democrats abandoned the bill in large numbers after key congressional negotiators bowed to a veto threat by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and agreed to hide 60 percent of the bailout's cost from the federal deficit. But with the losses of government-insured deposits mounting at a rate of $ 20 million to $ 30 million daily, <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> leaders from both parties _ with vigorous personal lobbying by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> over the telephone _ put together enough votes to replenish an insolvent S & amp; L insurance fund with $ 50 billion. `` The savings of million of Americans are at stake unless we do something,'' Sen. <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Bond </PERSON>, R-Mo., said just before the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> approved the bill on a non-roll call late Thursday night Rep. <PERSON> Chalmers </PERSON> <PERSON> Wylie </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ohio </LOCATION>, said the nation risked `` another bank holiday'' similar to the wave of bank closings of 1933 when depositors lined up for blocks demanding their savings, turning what was then a recession into the Great Depression. The $ 50 billion will be used over the next three years to close and merge 500 insolvent S & amp; Ls and pay off depositors whose savings were lost to failed and often fraudulent loans over the past decade, most of them in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. The legislation also overhauls the regulation of the industry, requiring owners of the nation's 3,000 thrift institutions to put up billions of dollars more of their own money as capital to serve as a buffer between risky loans and federal deposit insurance funds. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the administration had worked out the reforms weeks ago, leaving the sticky issue of how to pay for the bailout without raising taxes or dipping into other government programs as the major roadblock to fixing the S & amp; L crisis. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> insisted that the money be raised through an elaborate scheme using non-Treasury bonds to be issued by a new government agency created only for that purpose as a way of keeping the bailout costs out of the government's official deficit figures. Democrats demanded that the money be borrowed directly through the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>, a move that would have swelled the deficit by $ 44 billion over three years but would have reduced the 30-year interest costs on the borrowing by $ 4.5 billion. After <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on Thursday threatened to veto the bill if it ballooned the deficit, the two sides agreed to split the financing both ways. Under an accord hammered out by <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> and White House Budget Director <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Darman </PERSON> with key lawmakers, the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> will borrow $ 20 billion before October, swelling the estimated deficit for this year from $ 148 billion to $ 168 billion. But the non-Treasury bonds will be used to raise the other $ 30 billion in 1990 and 1991, raising the deficit a maximum of only $ 3.5 billion _ the annual interest payments on the borrowing _ each of those years if current interest rates prevail. Just before the vote today, Rep. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Gibbons </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, one of 135 House Democrats voting against the bill, complained his colleagues had lost their conscience and their backbone in response to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s veto threat. `` It should have been paid for by taxes, but the president could not bring himself to say the word,'' said <PERSON> Gibbons </PERSON>. `` So we have fostered this unconscionable debt on our children and grandchildren.'' By the administration's latest estimates, the bailout is expected to cost $ 159 billion _ including interest on the borrowing to pay for it _ over the next 10 years. Over 30 years, the costs mushroom to $ 285 billion, of which taxpayers will pay at least $ 157 billion, according to the congressional auditors in the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>. The bill also requires S & amp; Ls to channel more of their lending to home mortgages and away from speculative commercial real estate ventures and high-yield, high-risk junk bonds. It gives the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> $ 75 million a year to root out fraud at financial institutions and establishes a new agency, the <ORGANIZATION> Resolution </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, to dispose of $ 300 billion of real estate and other property falling into the government's hands through failed S & amp; L loans. For the first time, banks will be able to buy and own healthy S & amp; Ls, their biggest lending market competitor in many communities. And the thrift industry will be required to pour $ 50 million to $ 100 million of its profits each year into subsidizing mortgages at below-market interest rates for low-income families.
</TEXT>
