<FIRST>r a PM-CannibalismStudy     08-05 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cannibalism Study,0545</SECOND>
<HEAD>Researchers Say Cannibalism Victims 115 Years Ago Were Carefully
Defleshed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Alferd is cq.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TCC1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR H. ROTSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The five miners who prospector-cannibal <PERSON> Alferd </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Packer </PERSON> fed upon in the winter of 1874 were viciously beaten to death and their bones picked clean of flesh with knives, researchers say `` The pangs of starvation can not adequately and totally account for the brutality manifested in these killings,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Starrs </PERSON>, a professor of law and forensic science at <ORGANIZATION> George </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. `` What we have seen is not merely murder but butchery, a butchery at once wholesale, remorseless, unremitting and deliberate,'' he said at a news conference Friday. <PERSON> Starrs </PERSON> organized a scientific inquiry that last month unearthed the bones of the five men in the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Juan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION> of southwestern <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>. The expedition was launched to solve one of the grisly mysteries of the Old West, the story of <LOCATION> Packer </LOCATION> _ a harness maker, guide and prospector from <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> _ and the men he ate. A team of 13 scientists and anthropologists using radar-mapping equipment recovered the remains two miles south of <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Packer </PERSON> and five other gold-seekers became snowbound on a 9,000-foot-high pass in February 1874 <PERSON> Packer </PERSON> walked out of the mountains the following April. In his confession, he admitted having eaten the others to survive, but said he had shot one of the men, <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> <PERSON> Bell </PERSON>, in self-defense when he returned to camp and found <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> had murdered the other four with a hatchet. `` There is no visible evidence for gunshot wounds on any of them,'' said <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Birkby </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Identification </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION> and curator of physical anthropology at the <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Birkby </PERSON>, a forensic anthropologist, initially had said last month there appeared to be a bullet hole in one pelvic bone. But he said laboratory examination showed it to be a hole caused by the canine tooth of a flesh-eating animal. <PERSON> Birkby </PERSON> said the youngest victim, believed to be 17 or 19, was beaten the most severely. `` He was hit at least 11 times in the head with an axe.'' The young man's shattered upper left arm suggested that he had been able for a time to fend off his attacker. The victim would have been in better shape, stronger and perhaps better able to withstand the rigors of starvation and temperature than his older co-victims, the oldest of whom was between 50 and 60, <PERSON> Birkby </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Starrs </PERSON> said: `` Someone had an insatiable hunger. Whether for human flesh or not I am not about to say. This was not mindless cannibalism in any sense. These bodies were denuded of their flesh in a concerted and calculated way.'' <PERSON> Packer </PERSON> escaped from custody but was captured in 1883 in <LOCATION> Cheyenne </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wyo. </LOCATION>, and was convicted of murdering one prospector and sentenced to hang. The sentence was overturned on a technicality and on retrial he was convicted of manslaughter and given a 40-year prison sentence. <PERSON> Packer </PERSON> died in April 1907, six years after he was paroled. <PERSON> Starrs </PERSON> said the bones will be reinterred Aug. 14 at <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
