 A previously unknown group claimed in a statement published today that a man killed in a <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> hotel explosion was preparing an attack on British author <PERSON> Salman </PERSON> <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON>. <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON> has been in hiding in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> since Feb. 14, when the late Iranian leader <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> said his novel `` The Satanic Verses'' blasphemed Islam and called on Moslems to kill the author. <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> Yard said a man was killed Thursday as he worked with a handmade explosive charge inside a <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> hotel near <LOCATION> Paddington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Station </LOCATION>. The statement from a group calling itself the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Islam </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Mujahedeen </ORGANIZATION> did not identify the man, which it said was the group's `` first martyr.'' `` Others would follow his example to try to kill <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON>,'' said the statement published in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s leading newspaper, An-Nahar. `` Henceforth, we warn all those who supported and facilitated <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON>'s works and helped publish the satanic book to back off because our hand will reach out for them all,'' the group said. The statement called on British authorities to preserve the dead man's body, saying it would make arrangements to recover it later. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, a spokesman for <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Yard </LOCATION> said police were discounting claims that <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON> was the intended target of the bomb. The dead man, the only victim of the Thursday blast at the 18-room <ORGANIZATION> Beverley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Hotel, had been staying there for several days, police said. He was believed 