<HEAD>Cardinal Urges Black Catholics Not To Break From Church</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CURT ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Cardinal <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> told black Roman Catholics the church needs to rid itself of racism, and appealed to them not to be led out of the <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> by false leaders. `` How many phonies are there? How many people can you trust when you put them in positions of leadership?'' the cardinal said Friday before about 250 people attending a four-day conference of black Catholics. The hottest topic of conversation at the conference is the Rev. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Stallings </PERSON>, a black <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> priest who has formed a separate church that combines Catholicism with African and black American religious traditions. Of <PERSON> Stallings </PERSON>, <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> would say only that he is `` praying for everybody involved'' and is leaving the priest's fate up to local church authorities. The church has suspended him from performing sanctioned Masses and other sacraments but has not moved to excommunicate him. <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> implored black Catholics not to let racial questions force them from the church. `` The church can not be exclusive, whether it's exclusively white, exclusively black, exclusively yellow,'' <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> said. `` We are all one in the body of Christ.'' The conference, whose theme is `` Creating a Spirit of African-American Leadership,'' centers on ways to eliminate racism in the church and bring more blacks into top church positions. Archbishop <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Marino </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, the first black archbishop in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, said he was saddened at the schism highlighted by <PERSON> Stallings </PERSON>' break, but he pointed to himself as evidence that blacks can attain power within the hierarchy. `` The majority of us intend to stay in the church and bring about change, and a lessening of racism,'' <PERSON> Marino </PERSON> said. Still, <PERSON> Marino </PERSON> said <PERSON> Stallings </PERSON> might accomplish some good with his boldness. `` I think it has shown the leadership of the church that there are these concerns,'' <PERSON> Marino </PERSON> said. A spokeswoman at <PERSON> Stallings </PERSON>' church, the <ORGANIZATION> Imani </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION>, said Thursday the priest had no plans to attend the conference, held by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholics </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lay </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION>. The groups represent more than 1 million black Catholics. One speaker during the conference, <ORGANIZATION> Morehouse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> history professor <PERSON> Giles </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Conwill </PERSON>, said <PERSON> Stallings </PERSON> could boost black efforts to improve their standing in the church. `` We may not agree with his method of leaving the church but he is a catalyst,'' <PERSON> Conwill </PERSON> said. In his speech, <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> stressed that leaders of black Catholics or of any other ethnic group must not try to teach their own version of Christianity. `` There are some people ... campaigning for all sorts of things who will promise you a pie in the sky,'' <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> said. `` But are they leading where God wants people to be led?'' The cardinal said church leadership could do more to expunge racism from its congregations. `` The church leadership must make racism a priority,'' <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> said. `` We must get rid of racism in the hearts of Catholics.''
