<HEAD>New News Shows Premiere to Varied Response, Good Ratings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The premieres of <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s and <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>'s new prime-time news shows resulted in mixed reviews but relatively good ratings. <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Yesterday, Today and Tomorrow'' made its bow Wednesday to negative reviews for its cheesy special effects, dull stories and use of re-creations to illustrate some of its stories. But the reviews did n't deter viewers. Twenty-two percent of the viewing audience opted for `` <ORGANIZATION> YTT </ORGANIZATION>,'' putting it several points ahead of reruns on <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- `` Wiseguy'' -RRB- and <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- `` <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>'' -RRB-. It did as well or better than the parade of entertainment shows <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> has tried in the time period, which no one network has dominated. `` Yesterday, Today and Tomorrow'' is getting a three-week summer tryout, but is n't on <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s fall schedule. The much more highly publicized debut of <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` PrimeTime Live,'' pairing <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Donaldson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Diane </PERSON> <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON>, formerly of <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION>, got good-to-so-so notices. `` Prime-Time Live'' is a weekly series from here on out. Though it came in last in its time period in the Nielsens, `` PrimeTime Live'' was a dramatic improvement for <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>, which has been unable to make any headway against <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> powerhouse Thursday lineup with entertainment programming, such as `` HeartBeat.'' Most recently, low-rated `` Thursday Night Baseball'' was in the time period. `` PrimeTime Live'' drew 18 percent of the viewing audience. <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> normally gets about an 11. A rerun of <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` L.A. Law'' got 21, as did the movie on <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION>, `` Outback Bound.'' <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> TV critic <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Shales </PERSON> praised `` PrimeTime Live,'' saying, `` Network television experienced a welcome electrical charge last night.'' He called the premiere `` one of the smoothest maiden voyages in television history.'' Other critics were less enthusiastic. <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Goodman </PERSON>, writing for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Donaldson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> `` made a workmanlike team.'' He said, `` No potatoes will be knocked off their couches,'' but dubbed the premiere `` a respectable effort.'' <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Sonsky </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Miami </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> called it `` a good college try, but not a must-see yet.'' The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Bianculli </PERSON> was not impressed at all. `` This is a show,'' he said, `` that started out with more flash than substance and with more desperation than direction.'' The critics were pretty unanimous, though, in criticizing the <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> program, which featured three co-anchors _ <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Shriver </PERSON>; <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Alice </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, recently acquired from <ORGANIZATION> CNN </ORGANIZATION>; and local <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> anchor <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Scarborough </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> critic <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosenberg </PERSON> started out his review, `` This is a re-creation,'' then constructed a fictional _ and unflattering _ account of what the three anchors might have been saying when watching the show: `` Scarborough: God, I'm a commanding figure. Notice how I speak deeply and earnestly, my granite chin thrust toward the camera just so, implying strength and authority. My eyes have never sparkled like this before. And I'm having such a good hair day, I can hardly stand it.'' <PERSON> Rosenberg </PERSON>, like other critics, was especially bothered by the network news program's use of re-creations, a device identified in recent months with syndicated news programs of questionable journalistic integrity. `` Do n't the news divisions realize they have enough of a credibility problem without shooting themselves in the knee this way?'' wondered <PERSON> Shales </PERSON>. As for the program itself, he said, `` If you called it journalism as entertainment, you'd be stretching both terms.'' Concluded <ORGANIZATION> Fort </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Worth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Star-Telegram </ORGANIZATION> critic <PERSON> Art </PERSON> <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON>, `` <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> was not any good at putting together a newsmagazine show yesterday, it's not any better today. It would be foolish to assume they can do better tomorrow.''
