<HEAD>Telephone Workers in 24 States Prepare For Possible Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR ALLEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Four regional phone companies faced possible strikes tonight pending negotiations with unions representing 226,000 telephone operators, linemen and other communication workers in 24 states. <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> NYNEX </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> BellSouth </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Telesis </LOCATION> were holding separate talks with workers represented by the <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brotherhood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electrical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> on the contracts that expire at midnight. The main differences were over health benefits; each of the four companies, trying to save on medical and insurance bills, were trying to get unionized employees to pay a larger percentage of their medical bills. The four phone groups are among the seven so-called Baby Bells that were created as a result of the 1984 <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T breakup. `` We're in what I would call tough negotiations; they're going to be negotiating quite heavily in trying to meet that deadline,'' said <PERSON> Vira </PERSON> <PERSON> Milirides </PERSON>, spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION> CWA </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Oakland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>. Workers may stay on the job past the deadline if the issues are close to settlement, she said <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Jill </PERSON> <PERSON> Foley </PERSON> said the company was hopeful about reaching agreement with the union, which represents 44,000 workers in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and 6,000 in <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION>, 90 percent of the non-management work force. <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bell </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Nevada </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> together form <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telesis </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Milirides </PERSON> said the group wants employees to start paying a percentage of their health benefits, previously paid entirely by the company, and is offering wage increases of about 5 percent over three years, which the <ORGANIZATION> CWA </ORGANIZATION> says is insufficient. Pay ranges from about $ 228 a week for some operators to $ 650 for skilled technicians, <PERSON> Milirides </PERSON> said. Similar issues were being debated on the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>, where <ORGANIZATION> NYNEX </ORGANIZATION>, the telephone company for <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, on Friday raised its offer on health insurance in talks with the two union locals representing 60,000 workers. But <PERSON> Myles </PERSON> <PERSON> Calvey </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> IBEW </ORGANIZATION> Local 2222 in <LOCATION> Quincy </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, said he doubted the offer would avert a strike. `` It amounts to about $ 2 a week,'' he said. `` It's not a substantial increase. It's not something we can accept.'' He said many employees joined the telephone company because of its generous benefits. `` The membership is really 100 percent behind us on this one,'' <PERSON> Calvey </PERSON> said. `` Most employees could understand if the company was in some kind of a financial problem, but they've made record profits.'' <ORGANIZATION> NYNEX </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON> said hundreds of management personnel are ready to take temporary assignments to maintain service in the event of a strike, and he predicted that customers would barely notice, since most telephone operations are automated. But <PERSON> Calvey </PERSON> contended that customers would quickly see a decline in service if the unionized operators, service technicians, linemen and clerical workers walked off their jobs. Other down-to-the-wire contracts were taking place in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, where <ORGANIZATION> BellSouth </ORGANIZATION> was negotiating with the <ORGANIZATION> CWA </ORGANIZATION> on contracts for 64,000 workers in nine states, and in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, involving the more than 52,000 <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> employees in six <LOCATION> mid-Atlantic </LOCATION> states and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>.
