<FIRST>r i PM-Indonesia-Earthquake     08-05 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Indonesia-Earthquake,0307</SECOND>
<HEAD>Death Toll From Quake Rises to 116</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rescue teams have found 19 more bodies, bringing to 116 the death toll from an earthquake that triggered landslides in the country's easternmost province, a government official said today. The Social Affairs Ministry official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said rescue workers retrieved the bodies Friday from under demolished houses and masses of earth in the village of <LOCATION> Soba </LOCATION>, in the mountainous district of <LOCATION> Kurima </LOCATION>. Soba was the hardest hit of three villages, including <LOCATION> Holuan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pasema </LOCATION>, nearest the quake's epicenter 219 miles south of the provincial city of <LOCATION> Jayapura </LOCATION>, 2,188 miles east of <LOCATION> Jakarta </LOCATION>. The official said workers also rescued 20 injured people who were trapped in the rubble of mountain slopes that were crumbled by Tuesday's quake, which measured 6 on the Richter scale. The scale is a gauge of the energy released by an earthquake as measured by the ground motion recorded on a seismograph, and every increase on the scale means the motion is 10 times greater. A magnitued of 6 can cause severe damage. Authorities have evacuated more than 700 people from the stricken area, which has a population of about 3,500 people, the official said. `` Rescue workers still are busy searching for missing villagers,'' he said via telephone from <LOCATION> Jayapura </LOCATION>. He could not say how many remained missing, however. An official of the <ORGANIZATION> Meteorology </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Jakarta </LOCATION> said an earthquake with a magnitude of 5.2 shook the southern coast of west Java on Friday, but that there were no reports of casualties or damages. He said the quake was centered in the <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION>, 100 miles south of <LOCATION> Jakarta </LOCATION>. In 1981, more than 300 people were killed in <LOCATION> Kurima </LOCATION> by an earthquake measuring 6.8 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale.
