<HEAD>Bolivian Congress Elects Paz Zamora as President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jaime </PERSON> <PERSON> Paz </PERSON> <PERSON> Zamora </PERSON>, the third-place finisher in May elections, was elected president of <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION> following an all-night debate in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, officials said today. <PERSON> Paz </PERSON> <PERSON> Zamora </PERSON> garnered 98 of the 156 votes after former dictator Gen. <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON> <PERSON> Banzer </PERSON> <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> cast his support to the 50-year-old. <PERSON> Paz </PERSON> <PERSON> Zamora </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Left </ORGANIZATION>, had been arrested by <PERSON> Banzer </PERSON> in 1974 and accused of trying to overthrow the government. <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Ossio </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanjines </PERSON>, an ally of <PERSON> Banzer </PERSON> and head of the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, was elected vice president. Swearing-in ceremonies for the Bolivian leaders' four-year terms is scheduled for Sunday afternoon. The opposition had held up balloting because of alleged voting irregularities in the May 7 election. No candidate received a majority in the voting, so under <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION>'s Constitution, the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> chose from the top three contenders. Squeezed out by the <PERSON> Paz </PERSON> <PERSON> Zamora-Banzer </PERSON> alliance was <PERSON> Gonzalo </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Lozada </PERSON> of the governing <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Lozada </PE