bassador <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gelbard </PERSON> said Friday, `` We expect to have a very good relationship with this government and <PERSON> Paz </PERSON> <PERSON> Zamora </PERSON> has indicated to me his interest in attracting foreign investments to <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Paz </PERSON> <PERSON> Zamora </PERSON> is the son of a career army officer. He attended a Roman Catholic seminary in <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> but then went to <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>, where he was active in university politics. When he returned to <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION> in 1971 he founded the Movement of the <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Left </ORGANIZATION> and advocated armed struggle to overthrow <PERSON> Banzer </PERSON>, who seized power in a coup in 1971. After he was released, <PERSON> Paz </PERSON> <PERSON> Zamora </PERSON> went into exile abroad. He came back to <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION> in 1977 and resumed his political activities. In 1980, his party formed a coalition with the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Leftist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION> under the leadership of <PERSON> Hernan </PERSON> <PERSON> Siles </PERSON> <PERSON> Zuazo </PERSON> and the coalition won the election. A military coup in July 1980 blocked the installation of <PERSON> Siles </PERSON> <PERSON> Zuazo </PERSON> as president and <PERSON> Paz </PERSON> <PERSON> Zamora </PERSON> as vice president. In 1982, the military stepped down and turned over the government to <PERSON> Siles </PERSON> <PERSON> Zuazo </PERSON>. <PERSON> Siles </PERSON> <PERSON> Zuazo </PERSON> and <PERSON> Paz </PERSON> <PERSON> Zamora </PERSON> stepped down in 1985, a year before their terms expired, because of social unrest and political pressure. During the <PERSON> Siles 