<HEAD>Britain Reports Fire on Nuclear Submarine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FASLANE, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An electric motor in a <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> nuclear submarine caught fire today while the vessel was berthed in <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, but crewmen quickly extinguished the flames, the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said. No one was injured, and no radioactivity leaked out, <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> officials said. The fire broke out shortly after midnight in an electric motor on the submarine HMS Valiant, a <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> said. The vessel had returned to its base in Faslane on the <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Clyde </LOCATION> in southwest <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> after a $ 88 million refitting. HMS Valiant, launched in 1963, is the <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s oldest nuclear-powered submarine. When on duty at sea, it is armed with surface-to-surface, conventional missiles and non-nuclear Tigerfish torpedoes. It carries a crew of 116. The spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity in keeping with British practice, said the motor that caught fire is part of the hydraulic system. He said the fire posed no danger to the crew or the nuclear reactor. `` It was nothing to do with the nuclear side of things. It was a mechanical problem. It was nowhere near the reactor,'' he said. The hydraulic system drives some equipment on the submarine, including the periscope and hatches. The spokesman said he had no details of damage or exactly how the fire started. However, he said crewmen put it out within 15 minutes.
