<SECOND>AM-Savoy Hotel, Bjt,0602</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Savoy, Rendezvous for the Rich, Celebrates 100 Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BEN DOBBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Johann </PERSON> <PERSON> Strauss </PERSON> conducted Viennese waltzes in its restaurant, <PERSON> Anna </PERSON> <PERSON> Pavlova </PERSON> danced in the ballroom, and <PERSON> Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Monet </PERSON> painted his impressionist views of the Thames from a fifth-floor suite. The Savoy, the distinctly English dream hotel, on Sunday marks 100 years of catering to high society, providing an opulent, discreet and dramatic rendezvous for celebrities, magnates, potentates and royalty. Modeled on the great American hotels of the day, the Savoy was built by impresario <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> D'Oyly </PERSON> <PERSON> Carte </PERSON> adjoining his Savoy Theater, home of the <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> operettas. From the outset, it was a byword for exclusivity. Princess <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON>, later <PERSON> Queen </PERSON> <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>, first danced here with Prince <PERSON> Philip </PERSON>. <PERSON> Winston </PERSON> <PERSON> Churchill </PERSON> got the word he had become prime minister at the Savoy and held War Cabinet meetings in the Pinafore Room. Gen. <PERSON> Dwight </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Eisenhower </PERSON> sent his dirty linen from the battle front. The Maharaja of <LOCATION> Patiala </LOCATION> had 3,000 roses delivered daily. Rock singer <PERSON> Elton </PERSON> <PERSON> John </PERSON> left his bath running and flooded three floors. `` Forty years ago, people were excluded mainly because of money,'' said <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, 78, author of `` The Savoy: A Century of Taste.'' `` There's now a more international flavor, an infiltration which rather destroys the ultra-snobbishness. `` The hotel is not snooty or over-introverted. It has kept a good balance. You've got your dukes and your Sinatras, and they seem to mix very well together,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said in an interview. Single rooms go for 140 pounds, or $ 224 a night, while a suite can cost as much as 520 pounds, about $ 832. When it opened in 1889, the Savoy was a wonder of the Victorian age, with 24-hour room service, speaking tubes on every floor, and 67 bathrooms at a time when its most luxurious rival, the <LOCATION> Victoria </LOCATION>, had just four. <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilde </PERSON> scorned the built-in washstands, saying that if he wanted hot water he would ring for it. All 202 rooms have buttons marked waiter, valet and maid. The hotel still insists on its own custom-made mattresses, pure linen sheets and towels. It keeps separate kitchens on all eight floors and decorates no two rooms the same, using Art Deco and traditional English country styles. The reservation office keeps 120,000 file cards listing the needs and idiosyncrasies of regular visitors. A staff of 650 attends to 300 guests, who in an average year order 350 pounds of caviar, 9,500 sides of smoked salmon, 52,000 oysters and half a ton of foie gras. Requests are almost never too eccentric. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinatra </PERSON> hankered after an espresso machine, so the manager bought one for him. An Italian marquise required live rabbits to feed his roommates, a pair of boa constrictors. In 1905, a South African millionaire flooded the forecourt to recreate a Venetian canal, and <PERSON> Enrico </PERSON> <PERSON> Caruso </PERSON> serenaded from a gondola. The Maharaja of <LOCATION> Patiala </LOCATION> booked 35 rooms and installed a silver bathtub and a private elevator in scarlet and gold lacquer. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> golf champion <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Hagen </PERSON> started a tradition of driving golf balls off the roof into a barge on the Thames. Asked how long he would be staying, <PERSON> Groucho </PERSON> <PERSON> Marx </PERSON> snapped, `` Till it stops raining.'' But a visitor from <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> who bought a bulletproof vest and summoned a waiter to test it was politely turned down. Weekend celebrations include a birthday ball, a tea party and fair for 320 disadvantaged children, and a firworks display over the Thames.
