reported from Chernobyl. Pick up 10th pvs, `In the...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> today disclosed for the first time that 20 people died and 1,200 suffered radiation-related illnesses in nuclear accidents from 1980-85. The official <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> quoted <PERSON> Luo </PERSON> <PERSON> Guozhen </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> as saying <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> needed stricter control over the handling of radioactive waste and that the government plans to build more disposal sites to handle the material. Several accidents involving nuclear waste have been reported in the past, but there have been no official disclosures of deaths. <PERSON> Luo </PERSON> told the paper that ignorance about the dangers of nuclear materials and managers who ignored regulations on handling radioactive waste had caused radiation leaks. In February, the <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> reported an accident that occurred last December, when some uranium was lost from a factory and 15 people were exposed to radiation. One man suffered third-degree burns, the report said. In 1986, an article by <PERSON> Zhou </PERSON> <PERSON> Zhumou </PERSON> at the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> said there were cases of exposure to radiation when <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s nuclear industry started up in the mid-1950s. It said that during the 1966-76 Cultural Revolution, when scientists and technology were ridiculed in political campaigns, a serious accident took place at a production reactor in northwestern <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Zhou </PERSON> said that about 10 people suffered from overexposure to radiation in that accident and that another man got uranium poisoning in an accident in 1973. But he said there had been no cases of acute radiation sickness. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has reported 31 deaths from the 1986 <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION> nuclear accident. In the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, one man died in an accident in 1986 at the <ORGANIZATION> Kerr-McGee </ORGANIZATION> atomic plant in <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> and three people were killed by radiation at an experimental reactor in <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> in 1961. The <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> also reported that <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> plans to begin construction of nuclear waste sites in eight provinces to handle its growing production of radioactive material. Nuclear dumps already have been built in 12 provinces, it said. It quoted <PERSON> Luo </PERSON> as saying the only major regions that will not have waste storage sites after 1990 would be <LOCATION> Hainan </LOCATION> island and <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION>. He said the facilities are needed to handle waste produced by about 1,000 industries and research establishments across the country. Most of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s nuclear waste so far has been generated by the military, but growing amounts are being produced by scientific labs, hospitals and non-military industries. Adding to the waste storage problem is the planned December start-up of the <LOCATION> Qinshan </LOCATION> nuclear power plant in <LOCATION> Zhejiang </LOCATION> and the 1992 scheduled opening of the <LOCATION> Daya </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> plant in southeast <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Guangdong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Province </LOCATION> Earlier this year, the paper reported that <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> was making plans for its first permanent nuclear waste dumps to be built in the coastal <LOCATION> Zhejiang </LOCATION> province and in northwest <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. The report in February quoted <PERSON> Pan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ziqiang </PERSON>, director of the safety department of the state <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, as saying that so far all of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s nuclear wastes have been put in concrete basement facilities and those sites only protect the material for about 10 years. Today's report did not describe the facilities being built.
