<HEAD>Florida Attraction Looking For a Few Good Mermaids</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEEKI WACHEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The mermaids of legend glided effortlessly through the seas, tempting mortals with their beauty and grace. It's not so easy in real life. At Weeki Wachee Spring, hundreds of young women apply each year, but few show the needed athletic skills, fearlessness and good looks to perform far under water at one of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>'s oldest tourist attractions. `` It's tough, there is no doubt about that,'' said <PERSON> Genie </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON>, mermaid supervisor. `` We have some strict requirements and only a few of the ` girls' actually go on to become mermaids.'' Forty-two years ago, the enormous freshwater spring with startlingly clear water, which extends more than 100 feet down, was turned into a tourist attraction. `` Mermaids'' wearing skin-tight suits that taper into a dolphin-like tail fin gulp air through hoses during the choreographed routines viewed by spectators in a subterranean amphitheater. `` We've done a lot of different things,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Young </PERSON>. `` We've eaten bananas and drank <ORGANIZATION> Coke </ORGANIZATION> underwater. We've recreated scenes from movies. One of the hardest things was eating a sandwich. It gets soggy pretty quick.'' But for beginners, `` I would say the toughest part is learning to only take in only about half a lungful of air,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Young </PERSON>, who performed as a mermaid from 1961 to the early 1970s. `` Otherwise, you will float to the surface.'' The attraction also features an exhibit of photos of living mermaids, and a shrine to swimmer-actress <PERSON> Esther </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>. Although never a Weeki Wachee mermaid, Ms. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> filmed a movie at the spring and made numerous guest appearances. Despite the specter of discrimination suits, Weeki Wachee remains extremely selective about its mermaids, who now number 26. Several attributes are manadatory: an attractive figure and at least shoulder-length hair, said Ms. <PERSON> Young </PERSON>. But even most of those with the right looks get shipped back to land following the swimming test. `` The first thing we look for is if you're afraid of the water,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Young </PERSON>. `` If you're nervous being underwater, forget it.'' Applicants must swim for 30 minutes, and perform simple underwater ballet and acrobatic moves, such as back flips and deep dives. The few that remain go on to begin serious training and instructions in how to use the air hoses and swim in various costumes. They start at $ 4 an hour and it may take up to a year to pass the apprentice stage, said Ms. <PERSON> Young </PERSON>. <PERSON> Marti </PERSON> <PERSON> Worsham </PERSON>, the veteran mermaid of the staff with 16 years of swimming behind her, recalls watching the mermaids swim around large flowers when she was a little girl. `` From then on, I always wanted to be a mermaid,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Worsham </PERSON>. `` I never expected I would one day be the one here the longest.'' At the end of a show, after the theater had emptied, a mermaid scrubbed algae from the windows with a steel-wool pad. A turtle swam nearby. `` This is part of the job the tourists do n't see,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Young </PERSON>. `` Cleaning up is n't part of the myth of the mermaid.''
