<HEAD>Congress Hands Bush Victory on First Major Legislative Initiative</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> ended a bitter, two-day parliamentary standoff early Saturday by adopting a $ 159 billion rescue of the savings and loan industry, handing President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> a victory on his first major legislative initiative. The bill, described as the most important financial law enacted since the Depression, provides money to close or merge an estimated 500 insolvent thrift institutions and to pay government obligations incurred in the rescue of 223 S & amp; Ls last year. The administration estimates the cost, including interest payments on bonds issued to finance the bailout, at $ 159 billion through 1999. At least half the money will be spent in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, where a combination of lax regulatory oversight and an economic downturn sent the industry's losses soaring. Much of the rest goes to other oil-producing states such as <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, and to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> where thrifts were permitted to enter businesses far removed from traditional home mortgage lending. `` It is without doubt the single biggest bill in the history of this country,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Jake </PERSON> <PERSON> Garn </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>, the ranking <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> member of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. In a series of what <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> calls `` never again'' provisions, the legislation overhauls the regulatory bureaucracy, imposes stringent financial and accounting standards on <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Ls and quadruples the maximum jail term for defrauding a financial institution. Analysts say the law will touch the lives of everyone who pays taxes, owns real estate or deposits their money in a thrift institution or bank. The shutdown of sick thrifts paying high interest rates likely will lower rates to all savers because healthy S & amp; Ls and banks have raised theirs to compete for deposits, economists believe. When the government moves to sell an estimated $ 300 billion in real estate inherited from failed S & amp; Ls, the glut of properties could depress prices in already fragile markets, primarily in the Southwest. Many lawmakers, sensitive to the public perception that they in effect are giving taxpayer dollars to crooks and con artists, said the bailout was the only way to protect millions of depositors whose accounts are federally insured up to $ 100,000. `` We are not bailing out S & amp; Ls, we are not bailing out their owners or stockholders. We are standing behind our promise to protect the savers of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Chalmers </PERSON> <PERSON> Wylie </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, the senior <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> on the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. Legislators, nevertheless, were reluctant to vote for the measure. But, about five minutes after midnight, the bill passed the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> by a 201-175 vote. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> had approved it less than two hours earlier in an unusual procedure that avoided a record of which members voted for and which against. Sen. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Riegle </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, D-Mich., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> banking panel, said the rare `` division'' vote, in which senators stand to cast their ballot, was used as part of informal arrangement that unsnarled a parliamentary tangle involving unrelated measures <PERSON> Riegle </PERSON> said the bill would have passed with about 70 votes had a roll call been taken. The S & amp; L bill, which runs to nearly 1,000 pages, is the first major piece of legislation initiated by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. Only two weeks after taking office, the president called on <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to act in 45 days to stem a financial emergency inherited from the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. It took <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> six months, but lawmakers gave <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> substantially what he wanted. The crisis had been building for years, but was little discussed in government outside of regulatory agencies and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' banking committees. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, and his Democratic opponent, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, virtually ignored the issue during the 1988 election campaign. The final dispute holding up passage had little to do with the S & amp; L problem and much to do with the political struggle between <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the administration over balancing the federal budget deficit. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> wanted to finance $ 50 billion of the program through a new, quasi-private agency, thus keeping S & amp; L spending from ballooning the federal budget deficit, which in turn would trigger automatic, across-the-board spending cuts under the Gramm-Rudman deficit reduction law. Democrats, trying to pressure <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> into reneging on his `` no new taxes'' pledge, wanted to embarrass the administration with climbing annual deficits. They would have avoided the spending cuts by simply waiving Gramm-Rudman. The White House claimed that would have set a precedent opening the way for a congressional spending spree on other projects. Democrats said their plan saves billions of dollars in interest costs because the government would borrow bailout money with regular <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> debt. On Thursday morning, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> threatened to veto the S & amp; L bill unless it included his funding plan. Shrugging off the threat, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> voted 221-199 to adopt the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> proposal. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, however, fell six votes short of the 60 needed to waive Gramm-Rudman and sent the legislation back to a conference between the two chambers. With the participation of Treasury Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> and Budget Director <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Darman </PERSON>, congressional negotiators worked out a compromise late Thursday night. Twenty billion dollars will be raised this year under the Democratic plan, inflating the deficit to about $ 168 billion, the highest in three years. The remaining $ 30 billion will be raised under the president's scheme, keeping the spending out of the deficit in 1990 and 1991. On Friday, opposition to the pact from two influential House chairmen, Rep. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ill </LOCATION>., of the <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, and Rep. <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Panetta </PERSON>, D-Calif., of the <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, jeopardized final `` There is a time to fold and there is a time to be bold,'' <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON> said, urging Democrats hold out for their plan through the early morning hours. But he and other speakers were interrupted with periodic shouts of `` Vote! Vote!'' from members anxious to follow their 51 colleagues who had already gone home. In the end, the lure of summer vacation proved more powerful. Enough Democrats folded to allow Republicans to pass the compromise.
