<FIRST>r w AM-S&amp;Ls-Glance     08-05 0648</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;Ls-Glance,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Highlights of S&amp;L Bill Adopted By Congress</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-S&amp;L Rescue Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> early Saturday voted final passage of a landmark savings and loan bill described as the most significant piece of financial legislation in 50 years. Here are the highlights of the bill:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>COST</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 According to the latest <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration estimate, the bailout will cost $ 159 billion through 1999. That includes $ 60.5 billion to meet government obligations incurred in the rescue of 223 S & amp; Ls in 1988, $ 74.2 billion to close or merge more than 500 additional S & amp; Ls and $ 24.4 billion for the government's share of interest on bonds sold to help pay for the bailout. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' General Accounting Office estimates the cost, with interest over 30 years, at $ 285 billion Of that, $ 157 billion will come from the taxpayers.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>CAPITAL</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 In the most important reform in the bill, <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L owners, 120 days after enactment, will be required to invest more of their own capital in their institutions. The provision, aimed at discouraging risky investments, requires owners to back every $ 100 they lend with $ 1.50 in tangible capital. By 1995, the standard will be $ 3. Many of the accounting loopholes that allowed <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L owners to avoid capital requirements have been closed.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>INSURANCE PREMIUMS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Both S & amp; Ls and commercial banks will pay more for the government deposit insurance that protects savers' accounts up to $ 100,000. Bank premiums will jump from 8 cents per $ 100 to 15 cents. S & amp; L premiums will rise from 20.8 cents to 23 cents. Analysts believe some of the expense will be passed on to savers.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>FINANCIAL STANDARDS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 The bill pushes S & amp; Ls back into home mortgage lending and out of risky investments such as speculative commercial real estate projects and junk bonds. Thrift institutions are required to raise the level of housing and housing-related loans in their portfolios to 70 percent, up from the current 60 percent requirement. S & amp; Ls currently involved in risky ventures will have five years to phase out their investments. After that, they can invest in those areas only through separately capitalized affiliates that involve no risk to insured deposits.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>BUREAUCRACY</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 The lead S & amp; L regulatory agency, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, is being dismantled. Its regulatory divisions will be transferred to a new agency within the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. The fund insuring S & amp; L deposits moves to the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deposit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which already insures commercial banks. The 12 regional <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banks </ORGANIZATION>, which are owned by the industry, remain independent. They will lose their regulatory power but continue to provide low-cost financing to S & amp; Ls.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>HOUSING</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 The industry-owned regional <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banks </ORGANIZATION> will be required to earmark $ 50 million a year, increasing to $ 100 million, to help finance housing for poor people.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ANTI-DISCRIMINATION</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Banks and S & amp; Ls will have to disclose reports from federal regulators evaluating how well they serve poor and minority neighborhoods. Mortgage lenders will be required to collect and disclose data on the race, sex and income level of customers and loan applicants.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>REAL ESTATE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 A new agency, the <ORGANIZATION> Resolution </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, will be created to sell more than $ 300 billion in real estate now owned by bankrupt <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Ls. The <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION> will do the work, overseen by a board headed by the treasury secretary. The government will be required to give housing authorities and non-profit agencies first chance to buy housing from the <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Ls. Some fear the massive property sales will further damage real estate markets in already-depressed oil-producing regions.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ANTI-FRAUD</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> is getting $ 75 million a year for the next three years to uncover and prosecute fraud at both S & amp; Ls and banks. It is directed to establish a special fraud task force in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, where most S & amp; L problems are centered. Maximum fines for financial institution fraud are being raised from $ 5,000 a day to $ 1 million and the maximum jail term from five years to 20 years.
</TEXT>
