<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Coal miners in the far northern <LOCATION> Vorkuta </LOCATION> region walked off their jobs Saturday but then agreed that government concessions are generous enough to keep them at work at least until next year, official reports said. The <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency said thousands of miners shut down 11 of 13 mines in the coal-rich <LOCATION> Pechora </LOCATION> field north of the <LOCATION> Arctic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Circle </LOCATION> but agreed to start working again at midnight after officials explained concessions included in a government decree. `` At a joint conference, representatives of mines and enterprises of the town unanimously decided to stop the strike until Jan. 1, 1990, and to start working from midnight,'' state TV reported. It did not say what would happen after the first of the year. Workers decided Friday to stay off the job until they received the full text of a government decree that officials say fulfills promises made to end a wave of strikes last month. The promises included bonuses for night work and for miners who use dangerous equipment, and better pension and overtime benefits. The government also made general pledges to improve housing and end shortages of food and consumer goods. A spokesman at the Organizational Department of the local <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> headquarters said in a telephone interview that <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Tsuryupa </PERSON>, a director of the state enterprise that operates all 13 mines, brought a copy of the decree from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, 1,100 miles to the southwest, and explained it to the workers Saturday. The miners then held a closed meeting to decide whether to go back to work, said the official, who declined to identify himself. `` Emotions have stabilized and now there are no outbursts,'' he said. Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> called last month's strikes by hundreds of thousands of coal miners the greatest trial of his 4 -LCB- years in power He sympathized with the workers but urged them to return to their jobs. Premier <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON> told the official media Friday that the settlement with the miners would cost about $ 3.2 billion. He said it would be difficult for the government to come up with the money and told other workers that if they strike they will hurt only themselves. `` If we follow the road of strikes, no one will benefit from it and low-paid sections of the population will be hit first,'' he said in a television interview. The <LOCATION> Vorkuta </LOCATION> miners first struck July 19, several days after thousands of miners in other parts of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> already had walked out. They demanded better living and working conditions and that the government pay more attention to the problems of workers in the far north. They returned to work after about a week. Workers in the <LOCATION> Kuzbass </LOCATION> area of <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION>, where the strikes began, conducted a two-hour warning strike Thursday because they said the government is not living up to its promise to shut down a hydroelectric project the miners say is damaging the environment.
