<HEAD>Algeria: Skilled Broker in Hostage Crises</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hostages, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 This Moslem Arab country has combined strong revolutionary credentials, good Western contacts, and deft diplomacy to forge a reputation as a successful mediator of hostage crises. It counts among its negotiating coups the release in January 1981 of Americans who were held hostage at the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Embassy in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. This North African country's envoys are once again playing the role of mediator: this time in the hostage crisis in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION> is no stranger to that country's turmoil. Though <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION>'s exact role never has been spelled out, <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> officials thanked the nation publicly after French hostages were released by pro-Iranian groups in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> in 1987-1988. `` We have a skill that we put at the disposal of the international community,'' the Algerian ambassador to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Sahnoun </PERSON>, told reporters in April 1988. He spoke after Shiite Moslem hijackers of a Kuwaiti jetliner gave up the plane in <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION> and were apparently allowed to escape. <PERSON> Sahnoun </PERSON> said he could not provide details of the agreement because it would break <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION>'s word to the hijackers and damage its chances of helping in such situations in the future. Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and former Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> criticized the decision to release the Kuwaiti hijackers, who killed two passengers. In response, <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION> rejected what it called an effort `` to fling discredit on an action which saved precious human lives from murderous violence.'' Perhaps the most prominent Algerian success came Jan. 20, 1981, when <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> hostages held 444 days in <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> stepped off an airliner at the <LOCATION> Algiers </LOCATION> airport. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> had cut a deal _ after months of mediation by Algerian diplomats. `` A happy ending might change the American view that we are communists,'' a senior Algerian official said at the time. After a war with <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> that led to independence in 1962, <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION> pursued socialist policies and shaped close ties with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and radical Moslem groups. While <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION> is often in clear sympathy with the aims of radical organizations, it has steered clear of supporting terrorist tactics. In October 1977, Algerian officials negotiated at the foot of a Japanese DC-8 hijacked by guerrillas from a group known as the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>. The Algerians helped win freedom for hostages in exchange for a $ 6 million ransom and the release of six of the militants' comrades in Japanese jails In this case, the hijackers also were apparently allowed to leave <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION>.
