<HEAD>100,000 Marooned In Floods</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HASAN SAEED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than 100,000 people were marooned, many on roofs, after rivers burst their embankments and caused floods that killed at least 150 people in the last two weeks, officials and news reports said Saturday. The torrential rains ended Thursday, and officials said river embankments had burst at 17 places, washing away mud-and-straw houses in at least 100 villages. They said floods had affected some 250,000 people. The area most severely hit was the tea-growing <LOCATION> Zakiganj </LOCATION> area in <LOCATION> Sylhet </LOCATION> district, 120 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Dhaka </LOCATION>, a Relief Ministry official said. The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said at least 10 people died of diarrhea in <LOCATION> Zakiganj </LOCATION> in the last three days. At least 1,000 others were affected by the disease caused by dirty drinking water, he said. News reports reaching <LOCATION> Dhaka </LOCATION> said at least 150 people died in the <LOCATION> Zakiganj </LOCATION> area as a result of the rains in the past two weeks. The government has sent 12 medical teams to <PERSON> Zakiganj </PERSON>. `` The situation is quite alarming. We are trying our best to evacuate the marooned people, but we do n't have enough speedboats,'' said an official who visited the area Friday. Many people were stranded on roofs with floodwaters around them, and some had built makeshift bamboo platforms, he said. `` Many people have grain, but they have no dry place to cook,'' he said. The Flood Forecasting Center said water was receding in the <LOCATION> Kushiara </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Zakiganj </LOCATION> but was still above the danger level. Flooding is an annual problem in this impoverished nation of 110 million. More than 1,400 people were killed last year in floods that submerged three-fourths of the country.
