cases.'' The North African country, which has strong ties to both the West and radical Moslem groups, has successfully mediated hostage crises in the past 10 years. Algerian diplomats helped win the release of American hostages in January 1981 after they were held 444 days at the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION>'s ambassador to <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Khaled </PERSON> <PERSON> Hasnawi </PERSON>, was quoted Saturday by <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> radio stations as saying his country was undertaking a new initiative to free all hostages. Radio Algiers said his talks involved all hostages, whether `` Lebanese, Palestinians, Americans, Europeans or Israelis.'' It cited `` progress in this mediation.'' Several <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> radio stations said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had specifically asked <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION> to intercede. A <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> statement issued in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> on Saturday demanded freedom from Israeli prisons of five `` uprising heroes,'' identified as <PERSON> Nidal </PERSON> <PERSON> Zaloum </PERSON>, <PERSON> Itaf </PERSON> <PERSON> Alyan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Abdul-Hadi </PERSON> <PERSON> Suleiman </PERSON> <PERSON> Ghanem </PERSON> and `` Lebanese resistance heroes'' <PERSON> Anwar </PERSON> <PERSON> Yaseen </PERSON> and <PERSON> Soha </PERSON> <PERSON> Bishara </PERSON>. It also demanded <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> release <PERSON> Obeid </PERSON>, Palestinians jailed during the anti-Israeli uprising in the occupied territories, and guerrillas it has captured.
