<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Eleven people have died in central and eastern <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> in June and July of a viral infection, and at least 140 other people have been hospitalized because of the illness, news reports said Saturday. The daily <ORGANIZATION> Politika </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ekspres </ORGANIZATION> said three people died in <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION> hospitals out of a total of nine diagnosed there as having the infection. Two people died in the town of <LOCATION> Pec </LOCATION> in the southern province of <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>, where several were reported afflicted with the virus known as `` mouse fever.'' Last month, the national news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tanjug </ORGANIZATION> reported a total of six dead and 126 hospitalized in central <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> from the disease, which is spread by field mice and other small rodents and their parasites. The symptoms include high fever, back and abdominal pains and redness of the face and eyes. Doctors advised people to wash produce, berries and mushrooms carefully and take precautions when outdoors. Experts have said the mortality rate in patients afflicted with the disease can be as high as 10 percent. They say there is no efficient drug or vaccine to treat it. Earlier press reports said the first cases this year of the disease appeared in May in the central republic of <LOCATION> Bosnia-Hercegovina </LOCATION>. There have been outbreaks of the disease in <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> also in 1961, 1967, 1968 and 1986.
