<HEAD>Plymouth Rock Beginning to Crack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PLYMOUTH, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Plymouth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rock </ORGANIZATION>, which attracts 1 million tourists a year, has started to crack open along the same line where a 1774 split was repaired in 1880. Tourists are n't likely to notice the crack but state officials are worried. They have approached local and state historical groups to coordinate the preservation of the rock. `` It's not a major task, and it's not expensive, but it's just such a very important landmark we do n't want to create any waves,'' said <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Matinzi </PERSON>, superintendent of Pilgrim Memorial State Park for the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION>. Waves crashing over the rock on the beach at <LOCATION> Plymouth </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION> are just what have caused the old mortar to erode and the rock to crack. In the 1880 repair job, the pieces never quite fit and the cement line was always visible. The rock weighs about six tons and is about 14 feet wide and 6 feet long. <PERSON> Matinzi </PERSON>'s plan involves digging out the sand to expose the total rock and then adding new mortar to hold the two pieces together. `` The poor rock has gotten knocked around so much, and it gets covered every tide,'' said <PERSON> Carolyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Travers </PERSON>, a research librarian at <ORGANIZATION> Plimoth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Plantation </ORGANIZATION>, which uses an old spelling of <LOCATION> Plymouth </LOCATION>. `` If they do n't do something, the froth will get in and split it.'' Legend, and some historians, have it that the first Pilgrim landing party used the rock to step ashore in December 1620. `` In December, wading is not high on the list of things to do,'' said <PERSON> Laurence </PERSON> <PERSON> Pizer </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Pilgrim </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>. `` The interest of the Pilgrims was to find a place to get off at a relatively high spot and there was no other obvious landing spot for several hundred feet north or south.'' The rock's troubles began when the Sons of <ORGANIZATION> Liberty </ORGANIZATION> decided to move it to the town square in 1774. The rock was dropped and broken, so they left two-thirds behind on the beach and moved one-third to town. But tourists kept chipping away at the smaller piece, so in 1880 it was taken back where it came from and the two sections patched together. The crack was n't all bad. At the time it occurred, locals saw the break as symbolic of the split between the colonies and <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
