<HEAD>Afghans Blame U.S., Soviet Union For Rocket Attacks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Joginder </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> grabbed a piece of shrapnel from a rocket that tore through his aunt's house Saturday, wounding his three young cousins, and demanded to know why the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> were allowing innocent Afghans to be hurt and killed. <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>'s relatives and the two young children of a neighbor playing in the front yard were among the latest victims of the rocketing of <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, an almost daily event since late June. <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Nabi </PERSON> <PERSON> Amani </PERSON> said 13 rockets pounded the capital Saturday, wounding eight people. During and after his briefing, at least four more rockets fell, their distinctive boom heard across much of the city. <PERSON> Amani </PERSON> said the rockets Saturday hit many areas but were concentrated around <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>'s main grain silo, where several hundred trucks loaded with wheat from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> were waiting to be unloaded. The rockets missed the silo, but one tore into the ground about a yard in front of a watchtower on its perimeter, breaking the tower's windows and those of nearby houses. For the last four or five months, <PERSON> Amani </PERSON> said, U.S.-backed guerrillas fighting to oust the Soviet-backed government have been trying to starve this city by cutting roads and preventing food deliveries. `` Now that they ca n't cut the roads and all these supplies are coming to the city, their attack is to destroy what has already been delivered. It is their aim to impose starvation,'' he said. The <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> family house is about 1 -LCB- miles from the silo. The home's metal roof was torn off, and a rocket's path could be traced through two-foo