 He has liberalized trade laws and taken other steps to enourage investment and exports, not just from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> but also from countries such as <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. Although <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials have been pleased by many of <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON>' actions, one said, `` They're not doing this to make us happy They're doing it because they think it will work.'' One remaining rub is patent law, with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies complaining that Mexican companies copy their products without compensation. But even there, officials said, progress is being made. While <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> got help on the debt, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials have been effusive in their praise for <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s efforts to combat drug trafficking. <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> has cracked down hard, arresting top traffickers and corrupt officials who had been untouchable for years. Mexican officials still argue, however, that the real problem is the demand for drugs in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Mexicans also criticize the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attitude towards <LOCATION> Mexican </LOCATION> immigrants, who they say are taking jobs Americans are unable or unwilling to fill. <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> has run some political risks in appearing to accommodate the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on so many issues. Few Mexicans forget for long that half of what was once <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> was conquered or bought by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Although <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> is now an urban society and the 13th largest industrial nation in the world, the psychological problems of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> condescension and Mexican sensitivity can still get in the way of normal relations.
