<HEAD>Rail Workers Stop Trains in Pay Dispute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rail workers in southwestern <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> stopped trains for an hour Saturday in their latest bid to pressure the government for pay increases to counter triple-digit inflation. The rail stoppage came as new Prime Minister <PERSON> Czeslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON> met with economic and political specialists from the opposition Solidarity movement in an effort to assemble a Cabinet. Former Prime Minister <PERSON> Mieczyslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON>, now first secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, conferred with party and army leaders Saturday, urging them to be proud of the party and defend it from `` demagogic attacks.'' <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> told the army officers meeting in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> that in the past the armed forces served as `` a strong support of people's rule The situation is the same today and I believe it will continue in the future.'' The rail stoppage between noon and 1 p.m. affected domestic rail traffic in the <LOCATION> Silesia </LOCATION> region except for certain trains taking children to summer camps, according to reports in the official media and from the <ORGANIZATION> Solidarity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. State television said about 80 trains were stopped. The strike was supported both by Solidarity and the official communist-allied trade unions. <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Renda </PERSON>, leader of a strike committee in <LOCATION> Katowice </LOCATION>, said rail workers now receive $ 60 a month in basic pay plus overtime and various differentials and bonuses. The workers want the basic pay increased to $ 96 a month along with cost-of-living adjustments recently approved by <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>. Management is offering to raise the basic pay to $ 84, but that would include a cost-of-living adjustment that has not yet been computed, state television reported. The average monthly income in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> is $ 127, according to government statistics. <PERSON> Renda </PERSON>, interviewed on state television, said, `` If our demands are not met, we expect the worse _ a general -LRB- railway -RRB- strike _ something that has never happened in the postwar period.'' Solidarity and the government media reported strikes by postal workers in <LOCATION> Legnica </LOCATION>, by workers at a tire factory in <LOCATION> Gruzdiaz </LOCATION> and by tram-car operators in <LOCATION> Walbrzych </LOCATION>. Strikes for higher pay have become common as the cost of living increases steadily. It is estimated the inflation rate for this year will exceed 120 percent. Gen. <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON>, who was turned down Thursday when he asked Solidarity Sen. <PERSON> Zofia </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuratowska </PERSON> to join his government, continued meetings with Solidarity lawmakers. <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON> met Saturday with Solidarity Deputy <PERSON> Ryszard </PERSON> <PERSON> Bugaj </PERSON> and opposition political theorists <PERSON> Bronislaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Geremek </PERSON> and Deputy <PERSON> Jacek </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuron </PERSON>.
