<HEAD>Judge Blasts HUD, Dallas in Public Housing Dispute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge, in a ruling that lambasted city and federal housing officials, said <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> helped create a segregated public housing system and must help pay to dismantle it. In his ruling Friday, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Buchmeyer </PERSON> blasted the federal <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION>, the city and the <ORGANIZATION> Dallas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> for what he called a `` long, unbroken history'' of segregation in housing. <PERSON> Buchmeyer </PERSON> accused the three of deliberately disrupting plans to correct the problem, and said he would appoint a special master to monitor compliance of a 1987 consent agreement handled in his court. `` The undisputed facts establish that the city was a substantial cause of deliberate racial segregation and discrimination in its public housing programs,'' <PERSON> Buchmeyer </PERSON> said. His ruling added the city to the list of defendants in a 4-year-old desegregation case against the housing authority and <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION>. He said he would rule later what financial share the city would assume. Seven black women sued in 1985, contending that thousands of federally assisted apartments in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> were segregated by race and unequal in conditions because of a longstanding pattern of discrimination by <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> and the city housing authority. The judge approved a settlement in January 1987 requiring demolition of most of the dilapidated <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> housing project and relocation of tenants to private, rent-subsidized apartments throughout <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> and the suburbs. Another part of his Friday ruling could have the effect of freeing up an estimated $ 3 million in federal funds for the demolitions. The funds were frozen by an amendment written by a <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> congressman to a <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> appropriations bill. <PERSON> Buchmeyer </PERSON> found that Mayor <PERSON> Annette </PERSON> <PERSON> Strauss </PERSON> and other city officials have chosen to ignore the 1987 decree. Attorneys for the plaintiffs said <PERSON> Buchmeyer </PERSON>'s ruling would lead to improvements for thousands of poor families living in federally financed slums. `` It's the first time a city has been ordered to join with a housing authority to desegregate its housing,'' said attorney <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON>. `` And it's the first time a city has been ordered to fund the remedies for the separate and unequal conditions it helped create.'' `` It's fantastic,'' said <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Dews </PERSON>, one of the plaintiffs in the case who has lived in subsidized housing for 20 years. `` There's a lot of people who say racism does n't exist in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, but this shows that it does,'' she said. Mrs. <PERSON> Strauss </PERSON>, contacted Friday while vacationing in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, would not comment on the ruling on the advice of the city attorney until the city council could be briefed. `` We have to hear what the attorney will recommend,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Strauss </PERSON> said. `` Until we know that, we do n't do anything.'' Assistant City Attorney <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Postell </PERSON> declined to comment, as did attorneys for the housing authority and <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Buchmeyer </PERSON> ruled unconstitutional a 1988 amendment by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Rep. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Frost </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>. It prohibits use of federal money for demolition of any of the nearly 3,500 apartments at the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> project. Under the court-approved settlement, 839 apartments in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> project were to be renovated and the rest demolished. Residents could seek alternate, privately owned housing with federal rent-subsidy certificates. The cost of the demolition was estimated at $ 20,000 per unit. <PERSON> Buchmeyer </PERSON> said the Frost Amendment was unconstitutional because it violated separation of powers. <PERSON> Frost </PERSON> said he felt the housing should be renovated rather than razed.
