<TEXT>
 About 1,000 demonstrators marched Saturday demanding the withdrawal of British troops from <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>, and police said 46 people were arrested when right-wing opponents confronted the marchers. Police moved in as a group from the right-wing <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> made their way to the march in north <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, which was organized by the <ORGANIZATION> Irish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Freedom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION> in advance of the 20th anniversary on Aug. 14 of the deployment of <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> troops in the province. The British <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> staged a counterdemonstration in central <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, and a group of marchers later went to the Irish march, police said. A <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> Yard spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity, said 39 of those arrested were from the right-wing march and seven were from the Irish march. British troops were deployed into the mainly Protestant province to control sectarian fighting. The mainly <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Irish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> is fighting to drive the British force from the province and unite it with <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>.
