<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> woman says the Lone <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION>'s official mammal and unofficial roadside distraction _ the armadillo _ could solve a flap over license plates <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Knox </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> that it should dump plans to put `` The Friendship State'' on <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> license plates and choose instead plates shaped like armadillos. Between the numbers and letters on the plate would be a star, representing <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>' standing as the Lone Star state. `` I think it's very realistic. It would be real neat,'' <PERSON> Mrs. </PERSON> <PERSON> Knox </PERSON>, 64, said Saturday. Since unveiling the design for `` The Friendship State'' plate last month, the highway department has been flooded with complaints from people saying the slogan does n't fit the spirit of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. Politicians have entered the controversy, saying the slogan is wimpy. `` If you have to advertise that you're friendly, forget it,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Knox </PERSON> said. `` I think it's terrible.'' She got the idea for the armadillo plate six years ago on a Canadian trip when she saw a license plate for the <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Territories </LOCATION> shaped like a polar bear. `` It was striking,'' she said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Between the baby bottle and the brown bag, there were lunch boxes. `` They were the first status symbols,'' said <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON>, 34, who has stirred the interest of baby boomers with a string of enterprises celebrating that old schoolyard standard in all its glorious incarnations. That Barbie doll box bought at the dime store for $ 3.49 back somewhere in the mid-1970s can fetch hundreds of dollars at auction these days. <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> collects and resells them. The Beatles, the Jetsons, <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> <PERSON> Mouse </PERSON>, <PERSON> Howdy </PERSON> <PERSON> Doody </PERSON> and even yesteryear's teen idol, <PERSON> Bobby </PERSON> <PERSON> Sherman </PERSON>, are also among the blue-chip boxes most highly prized by people generally between the age of 25 and 40, <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> said. About 120 million lunch boxes were sold in their heyday between 1950 and 1970. So, according to <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON>'s calculations, every baby boomer carried at least one, sometimes two, to school each year. `` By the end of the 1950s there were four competing lunchbox companies,'' <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> said. `` Kids had a choice of models that reflected their personalities, sort of like an automobile showroom.'' Now lunch boxes are available only in plastic. The last steel version, featuring Rambo, was pressed in 1987, phasing out the metal models more than a decade after a mother whose son got struck in the head with one brought and won a lawsuit banning them in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> saw the ban coming. He knew it was only a matter of time before baby boomers in search of nostalgia created a demand. He spent about $ 10,000 on his entire collection of 1,500 boxes and thermoses, a fifth of which he recently auctioned for $ 17,000.
