<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Opposition candidates won two of three seats contested for Parliament in multiparty elections Saturday, state television reported. In the third by-election race, the required number of voters did not participate and another election will be held. Although only three of 387 parliamentary seats were contested, the poor showing by the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> was considered an indication of voter sentiment before national multiparty elections planned for June. Low voter turnouts and the failure of a candidate to win a majority in by-elections on July 5 led to Saturday's round. By law, a turnout of more than 50 percent is mandatory and the winner must receive a majority of the votes cast. Less than 50 percent of the eligible voters turned out for the election at <LOCATION> Kiskunfelegyhaza </LOCATION> and another round will have to be scheduled, state television reported. The two winners were <PERSON> Ernoe </PERSON> <PERSON> Raffay </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Szeged </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Jozsef </PERSON> <PERSON> Debreceni </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Kecskemet </LOCATION>. They were backed by the Hungarian Democratic Forum, an alliance of political groups opposed to the ruling Communists. <PERSON> Raffay </PERSON>, a historian, defeated <PERSON> Karoly </PERSON> <PERSON> Miklos </PERSON>, a bus company manager who was the candidate of the Communists' reform wing, and <PERSON> Levente </PERSON> <PERSON> Dobozy </PERSON>, an independent. <PERSON> Raffay </PERSON> received 61.8 percent of the votes, <PERSON> Miklos </PERSON> 22.5 percent and <ORGANIZATION> Dobozy </ORGANIZATION> 16 percent. <PERSON> Debreceni </PERSON> ran unopposed after the Communist candidate and another rival dropped out following poor showings in the July 5 balloting. The evening newscast said <PERSON> Debreceni </PERSON> won 70 percent of the vote but did not account for the remaining 30 percent. The report said 57 percent of the electorate cast ballots in <LOCATION> Kecskemet </LOCATION> but did not give the turnout in the two other races. Leaders of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> made campaign appearances last week to help the party's candidates _ with little success. At a rally in <LOCATION> Kecskemet </LOCATION> Wednesday, party chairman <PERSON> Rezsoe </PERSON> <PERSON> Nyers </PERSON> said that although the elections would not determine the country's political future, they could not be ignored because they marked the beginning of a multiparty election system Lutheran clergyman <PERSON> Gabor </PERSON> <PERSON> Roszik </PERSON> won 69.2 percent of the votes in the July 5 by-election in <LOCATION> Goedoelloe </LOCATION>. He is considered to be the first opposition figure to be elected to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> since 1947, when the last completely free elections were held. Some non-communists won seats in 1985 under limited multiple-candidate elections but all candidates had to have the endorsement of the Communist-run <ORGANIZATION> Patriotic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>. That stipulation has been removed.
