<HEAD>New 50,000 Cordova Bill to Circulate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> will put a new 50,000-cordoba bill into circulation in an effort to keep up with steady devaluations and five-digit inflation that has forced some residents to carry bundles of money. Newspapers said Saturday that the new bill, worth about $ 2.50, will begin circulated Monday. The announcement comes less than four months after the government introduced the 20,000-cordoba note, the highest bill now in circulation. Since the beginning of the year, the cordoba has dropped from an official rate of 2,000 to the dollar to 20,000 to the dollar. The last devaluation was in June, when it fell from 9,500 to its current rate. Under a government austerity program this year, inflation has dropped from a rate of 20,000 for 1988. The rate for the month of July was 8.5 percent, according to official figures. However, prices on numerous basic products, including beans, cooking oil and soft drinks have increased substantially in the past few days. The new note carries the picture of <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Dolores </PERSON> <PERSON> Estrada </PERSON>, considered a national hero for his defeat of American adventurers <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> Cole </PERSON> and <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> and their militias on Sept. 14, 1856. On the reverse side, is the Hacienda <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jacinto </LOCATION>, the scene of the defeat.
