<DATELINE>SEYMOUR, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 This farm town, which claims it invented the hamburger, fried up a 5,520-pound patty Saturday and served it to about 10,000 people in a bid for a spot in the Guinness Book of World Records. `` It was nice and juicy,'' said <PERSON> Doris </PERSON> <PERSON> Witbrow </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Suamico </LOCATION>. The event at the <LOCATION> Outagamie </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fairgrounds </LOCATION> was a tribute to <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> `` Hamburger Charlie'' <PERSON> Nagreen </PERSON>, who _ according to local historians _ mashed a meatball to make the world's first hamburger in 1885. About 50 cooks in aprons worked around a specially designed grill 21 feet in diameter and heated by 12 gas burners. It took about two hours to cook the 6-inch-thick layer of ground chuck. To avoid having to flip the patty, grill designers <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Mielke </PERSON> and <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Sauer </PERSON> used a cover to cook both sides at once. A truck-mounted crane lifted the cover into place and suspended <PERSON> Sauer </PERSON> over the patty as he sprinkled salt. The burger was intended to serve 15,000 people, but the meat ran out after an hour and 45 minutes and 10,000 diners. Five thousand buns were left over. <PERSON> Seymour </PERSON> plans to submit its claim to the biggest burger to publishers of the Guinness Book. According to the Guinness Book, the largest hamburger on record weighed 5,005 pounds, 13.8 ounces and was cooked in <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Seymour </PERSON>, a town of 2,600 people 15 miles west of <LOCATION> Green </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>, disputes claims by other communities, including <LOCATION> Hamburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, to making the first burger. According to local lore, the 15-year-old <PERSON> Nagreen </PERSON> was selling meatballs from a booth at a fair when it occurred to him that people could carry them more easily if the meat were flattened between two slices of bread. The Appleton storekeeper died in 1951 after 65 years of hawking hamburgers at county fairs. The grill used to cook Saturday's giant hamburger was bigger than the patty, leaving space for a bigger attempt next year, said <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuehne </PERSON>, whose <ORGANIZATION> Green </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bay </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dressed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beef </ORGANIZATION> donated the meat.
