 Education Minister <PERSON> Toshiki </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaifu </PERSON> and two veteran politicians from the ruling party today applied to run in next week's election to choose the third prime minister in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> this year. Scandals involving bribery and sex have forced <PERSON> Noboru </PERSON> <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> and his successor, <PERSON> Sousuke </PERSON> <PERSON> Uno </PERSON>, from office prematurely. While the 58-year-old <PERSON> Kaifu </PERSON> remains the front-runner, some party leaders complained that he had been selected in backroom factional manuevers. Offended by those wanting reform pledges, two party veterans announced at the last minute Friday that they would challenge <PERSON> Kaifu </PERSON>. All three put in nomination papers shortly before the deadline this morning at the headquarters of the governing <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, which holds a secret ballot Tuesday to elect a successor to Prime Minister Uno.
