<FILEID>AP-NR-08-05-89 0649EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-CreditMarkets Adv07   08-05 0744</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Credit Markets, Adv 07,0770</SECOND>
<HEAD>adv07</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday, Aug. 7</HEAD>
<HEAD>Junk Bond Market Prepares For Fallout From S&amp;L Order to Divest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BART ZIEGLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The junk bond market is preparing for the fallout from a requirement that savings and loans sell their holdings in these high-yield, high risk investments as part of the congressional thrift bailout bill. Some industry watchers say the elimination of savings and loans as a market for junk bonds could depress junk bond prices and make it more expensive for companies to float new high-yield issues. `` It is a significant pool of capital that has now been cut off from the high-yield market. Of course that's going to restrict any market,'' said <PERSON> Greg </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>, executive vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Access </ORGANIZATION>, a trade group for junk bond issuers. Others say the ban on thrift junk bond holding may not have a major impact. `` While thrifts are important junk bond investors, they do n't comprise an enormous percentage of buying power,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kriz </PERSON>, an assistant vice president at <ORGANIZATION> Moody </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Kriz </PERSON> said other factors affecting the junk bond market at the time the thrifts sell their holdings may mitigate the effect of the sales. Among these factors are interest rates and how many new junk bond issues are floated. Other industry watchers say it's premature to say what effect the bailout bill's provision would have. The provision was approved by a <ORGANIZATION> House-Senate </ORGANIZATION> panel late last month. It would give thrifts five years to sell their junk bond holdings, so there probably would n't be a wholesale dumping of the bonds at once. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutions </ORGANIZATION>, the thrift industry's largest trade group, said it did not lobby against the junk bond requirement because only about 175 of the nation's 2,900 savings and loans invest in the bonds Of the 175, 10 held about 70 percent of the $ 4.1 billion in junk bonds owned by the industry in the first quarter, said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Grohl </PERSON>, a senior vice president for the trade group. The Alliance for Capital Access put the total junk bond investment by thrifts at about $ 14 billion. Whichever figure is correct, the investment is still a small fraction of the approximately $ 200 billion junk bond market. The Alliance's <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> says the loss of thrifts as junk bond buyers would be especially troubling because it has been a fast-growing market for the bonds. Thrift investments in junk bonds have doubled since 1985, he said. But, he added, there are other juicy markets for junk bonds that have barely been penetrated, such as the life insurance and mutual fund industries. Of the approximately $ 1 trillion in assets of life insurers, less than 1 percent is invested in high-yield securities. <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> said the ban on thrift junk bond holdings may have a psychological impact on the market, forcing junk bond issuers to increase the yields of the bonds, which already are substantially higher than <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bonds. But <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> said he expected the impact would be temporary. The savings and loan legislation provides a loophole for thrifts that want to keep their junk bonds. Under the bill, they may form a separately capitalized affiliate and sell their junk bonds to it. But <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> said few thrifts would have the financial wherewithal to set up such a subsidiary. Junk bonds are so named because they are rated as non-investment grade, or speculative, by the credit rating firms. Because of the higher risk of default, they pay more interest to holders than investment-grade bonds. Junk bonds are issued by companies that already are deep in debt or otherwise can not obtain an investment-grade rating. They also are used to raise cash for corporate takeovers. The Alliance for Capital Access stands by the soundness of junk bonds as investments. <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> said he believes the divestment provision of the bailout bill was motivated in part because the bonds are used for hostile takeovers and because thrifts were using federally insured deposits to invest in them. `` The debate was driven by emotion, not facts,'' <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> said. The pioneer and biggest booster of the junk bond market, <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, also opposes the divestiture requirement. `` No thrift has ever failed because of their investment in high yield bonds,'' said spokesman <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Anreder </PERSON>. `` We feel this action will only serve to restrict access to capital by small and medium-size businesses.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday, Aug. 7</NOTE>
