<HEAD>A Week That Would Make Edward G. Robinson Proud</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Restransmitting to fix release date at the bottom</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The word racketeer has acquired some new meaning in the high-living financial world, and it's not a name for the guy who strings tennis rackets at the country club. To a half-dozen securities professionals convicted in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and 46 futures traders indicted in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> under a tough law aimed at fighting organized crime, `` racketeer'' is like the ghost of <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Capone </PERSON>, a stigma that could plague them for the rest of their lives. If anyone in the lucrative business of buying and selling stocks, bonds and commodities still had any illusion they were somehow exempt from prosecution under this law, they likely were sobered by the events of this past week. Of particular significance were the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> convictions in the so-called Princeton-Newport case, based on what many attorneys had called confused and even flimsy evidence of fraud. This showed with dramatic certainty that juries will convict Wall Streeters under the racketeering law. It's an ominous sign for similar defendants facing trial, especially <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Milken </PERSON>, the ex-junk bond trader for <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> who faces far more serious charges. The Princeton-Newport case concerned a now-dissolved investment firm called <ORGANIZATION> Princeton-Newport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION>. Five of its members and another ex-Drexel trader were accused of creating phony tax losses via prearranged securities trades. Two days after the Princeton-Newport verdicts, prosecutors in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> announced long-awaited indictments stemming from a lengthy undercover probe of alleged fraud in the world's largest commodities markets. Again using the racketeering law, prosecutors accused the 46 defendants of turning the trading pits into their own private clubs where they reserved the best deals for themselves and tossed the dregs to unsuspecting clients. Both the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> prosecutions represent an aggressive application of the Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organization Act or RICO, as it's commonly called. It was enacted by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> nearly two decades ago to combat gangsters. The law is considered one of the most powerful enforcement tools ever enacted in this country, enabling prosecutors to seize a suspect's assets before trial and providing for crippling fines and lengthy prison terms upon conviction. Despite criticism from many lawyers that the law is excessive, its application has expanded over the years to prosecutions of criminal defendants ranging from union bosses to motorcycle gangs to politicians. The RICO acronym, also the name of the Capone-like mobster played by <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> in the 1930 film `` <PERSON> Little </PERSON> <PERSON> Caesar </PERSON>,'' was coined by one of the law's authors, <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Blakey </PERSON>, a Notre Dame law professor. `` RICO means crime is called by its correct name,'' <PERSON> Blakey </PERSON> once said. `` If people are running a racket, why should n't we try them for being a racketeer?'' In other business and economic news this past week: _ Convoluted economic reports sent confusing signals into the financial markets The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said its chief forecasting gauge fell 0.1 percent in June, the fourth drop in five months and a strong signal of a slowdown. But the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said unemployment dropped in July, suggesting the economy is growing stronger. _ Alleged sleazy business practices hurt the reputations of the nation's largest drug chain, charge-card company and home-shopping network <ORGANIZATION> Rite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and its president were indicted on charges they tried to bribe an <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> regulator. A top executive at <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> resigned for his role in trying to discredit a rival international banker through a smear campaign. <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shopping </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> was slammed with a $ 100 million defamation verdict for falsely claiming <ORGANIZATION> GTE </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> telephone mismanagement hurt its sales. _ In the takeover business, investor <PERSON> Irwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Jacobs </PERSON> knocked on <ORGANIZATION> Avon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Products </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s door with a $ 2.85 billion offer but the cosmetic giant rejected it; and <ORGANIZATION> Amax </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> agreed to buy <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Falconbridge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, in a $ 2.4 billion deal that would create one of the world's largest metal
</TEXT>
